{"title_page": "Henry Dalziel", "text_new": "{{about|the Australian recipient of the Victoria Cross|the British newspaper proprietor and politician|Henry Dalziel, 1st Baron Dalziel of Kirkcaldy}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name              = Henry Dalziel\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| image         = File:StateLibQld 2 93480 Private Henry Dalziel, V.C.jpg\n| image_size    = 175\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Private Henry Dalziel, c.1919\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=y|1893|2|18}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|1965|7|24|1893|2|18}}\n| birth_place   = [[Irvinebank]], Queensland\n| death_place   = Greenslopes Repatriation Hospital, [[Brisbane]], Queensland\n| placeofburial = [[Mt Thompson Crematorium]]\n| nickname      =\n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance    = Australia\n| branch        = [[Australian Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1915\u201319<br/>1933\u201343\n| rank          = [[Sergeant]]\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = [[15th Battalion (Australia)|15th Battalion (Queensland & Tasmania)]]\n| commands      = \n| battles       = First World War\n* [[Battle of Hamel]]\n* [[Battle of the Somme]]\n* [[Battle of Pozi\u00e8res]]\n* [[Battle of Mouquet Farm]]\n* [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]]\n* [[Battle of Passchendaele]]\n| awards        = [[Victoria Cross]]\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n}}\n'''Henry Dalziel''', [[Victoria Cross|VC]] (18 February 1893 \u2013 24 July 1965) was an [[List of Australian Victoria Cross recipients|Australian recipient]] of the [[Victoria Cross]] (VC), the highest award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to British and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] forces. He was awarded the VC while serving with the [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] during the [[First World War]]. Dalziel's VC was the 1,000th awarded. After the war, Dalziel returned to Australia and tried to make a living by farming. Troubled by the injuries he sustained during the war, he left the land and took up factory work. He moved between jobs several times during the 1930s, and led something of a transient lifestyle, even at one stage turning to gold prospecting. In the mid-1930s he rejoined the army in a part-time capacity and during the [[Second World War]] served in a training role in Australia. He died in 1965 at the age of 72.\n\n==Early life==\nHenry Dalziel, the son of a [[Queensland]] miner, was born on 18 February 1893 in [[Irvinebank]]. After completing his education he began working as a fireman on the railway.{{sfn|Mays|1981|pp=202\u2013203}}\n\n==First World War==\nDalziel volunteered for the [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] (AIF) in early 1915 and was posted to the [[15th Battalion (Australia)|15th Battalion]] as a reinforcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://discoveringanzacs.naa.gov.au/browse/person/141440 |title=Henry Dalziel \u2013 Discovering Anzacs |publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]] |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> He served throughout the [[Gallipoli Campaign]] until he was evacuated, along with the rest of his battalion, to Egypt in December 1915. From July 1916, he served on the [[Western Front (WWI)|Western Front]] in France and fought in the [[Battle of the Somme|Battles of the Somme]], [[Battle of Pozi\u00e8res|Pozi\u00e8res]] and [[Battle of Mouquet Farm|Mouquet Farm]]. His service continued into 1917, including the [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]] but he was wounded during the [[Battle of Passchendaele]] at [[Battle of Polygon Wood|Polygon Wood]]. He returned to the front in June 1918.{{sfn|Mays|1981|pp=202\u2013203}}\n\n[[File:Private Henry (Harry) Dalziel, awarded Victoria Cross.jpg|thumb|Private Henry Dalziel in England circa 1918, wearing a bandage under his hat]]\nIt was during the [[Battle of Hamel]] that Dalziel performed the deed for which he was awarded the Victoria Cross (VC). Assigned to the battalion's transport company as a driver, he volunteered to join the attack to make up for a manpower shortage that the battalion was experiencing at that time.{{sfn|Chataway|1948|pp=213\u2013214}} On 4 July 1918 at [[Hamel Wood]], when determined resistance was coming from an enemy strong-point which was also protected by strong wire entanglements, Dalziel, armed only with a revolver, attacked an enemy machine-gun. He killed or captured the entire crew and, although severely wounded in the hand, carried on until the final objective was captured. He twice went over open ground under heavy artillery and machine-gun fire to obtain ammunition and, although suffering from loss of blood, continued to fill magazines and serve his gun until wounded in the head.{{sfn|Laffin|1999|pp=77\u201378}}{{refn|Dalziel's personal account of the action was as follows: \"We were harassed by murderous fire from a nearby enemy stronghold, the Australian advance was held up. My gun had cleaned up one [machinegun] nest, but another planted in a different direction opened fire. I dashed at it killing seven Germans with my two revolvers. One German bloodhound wounded me in the hand, but I soon had him on the ground. I lunged at him with my German dagger, catching him right over the heart. His dying cry upset me and I shivered.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Barlass|first=Tim|title=World War I VC to go up for auction|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/world-war-i-vc-to-go-up-for-auction-20101113-17rul.html|journal=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=14 November 2010|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>|group=Note}} The citation for his VC, published in the ''[[London Gazette]]'', read:\n\n{{Quote|For most conspicuous bravery and devotion to duty when in action with a [[Lewis gun]] section. His company met with determined resistance from a strong point which was strongly garrisoned, manned by numerous machine-guns and, undamaged by our [[artillery]] fire, was also protected by strong wire entanglements. A heavy concentration of machine-gun fire caused many casualties, and held up our advance. His Lewis gun having come into action and silenced enemy guns in one direction, an enemy gun opened fire from another direction. Private Dalziel dashed at it and with his [[revolver]], killed or captured the entire crew and gun, and allowed our advance to continue. He was severely wounded in the hand, but carried on and took part in the capture of the final objective. He twice went over open ground under heavy enemy artillery and machine-gun fire to secure ammunition, and though suffering from considerable loss of blood, he filled magazines and served his gun until severely wounded through the head. His magnificent bravery and devotion to duty was an inspiring example to all his comrades and his dash and unselfish courage at a critical time undoubtedly saved many lives and turned what would have been a serious check into a splendid success.|The London Gazette, 17 August 1918<ref name='LonGaz'>{{London Gazette |issue=30849 |date=17 August 1918 |pages=9660\u20139660  |supp=y |city=l }}</ref>}}\n\nDalziel's VC was the 1,000th such medal to be awarded.{{sfn|Wigmore|1963|pp=129\u2013130}} His wounds were so severe that his brain was exposed and he was evacuated to England for medical treatment. It was not until January 1919 that he returned to Australia.{{sfn|Mays|1981|pp=202\u2013203}}\n\n==Later life==\nDischarged from the AIF in July 1919,{{sfn|Wigmore|1963|pp=129\u2013130}} the following year he married Ida Maude Ramsay, who had served as a nurse with the 17th Australian General Hospital. The couple took up a block of land for farming but his wife was primarily responsible for its running. After a few years, Dalziel tired of farming and moved to Sydney, where he took up factory work. His wife remained on the farm.{{sfn|Mays|1981|pp=202\u2013203}} He then tried his hand at gold mining in the [[Bathurst, New South Wales|Bathurst region]] before later returning to the farm when his wife became ill.{{sfn|Wigmore|1963|pp=129\u2013130}} By 1933, he was living in [[Brisbane]] but out of work.{{sfn|Mays|1981|pp=202\u2013203}} At this time, having maintained an interest in song writing since his time in hospital recuperating from his war wounds, he had some of his work published in England and the United States.{{sfn|Wigmore|1963|pp=129\u2013130}}\n\nFrom 1933, Dalziel served in the [[Australian Army Reserve|Citizen Military Forces]] and was a sergeant in the 9th/15th Battalion.  During the Second World War, he did not serve abroad. Instead he supported recruitment and funding drives. He also conducted talks for troops at training camps. His final posting before he was discharged from the Army in December 1943 was to the 11th Training Battalion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ww2roll.gov.au/Veteran.aspx?ServiceId=A&VeteranId=102074 |title=Dalziel, Henry |work=World War II Nominal Roll |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia |accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> In 1956, he travelled to England for the VC centenary celebrations.<ref name=Willey>{{cite web|last1=Willey|first1=Harry|title=Private Harry Dalziel|url=http://www.firstworldwar.com/features/dalziel.htm|publisher=firstworldwar.com|accessdate=12 September 2014}}</ref> In late life, Dalziel lived in [[Oxley, Queensland|Oxley]].{{sfn|Wigmore|1963|pp=129\u2013130}}\n\nOn 24 July 1965, Dalziel suffered a stroke and died at the [[Greenslopes Private Hospital]] in Brisbane. He was cremated with full military honours. A plaque in his memory is laid at [[Mount Thompson crematorium]], Brisbane.<ref name=Willey/>\n\n==Legacy==\nOn 25 November 2010, a group of Dalziel's medals and associated documents were auctioned by Noble Numismatics in Sydney, fetching AUD $525,000 + commission.<ref name=Noble>{{cite web|url=http://www.noble.com.au/auctions/lot?id=263759|title = Lot 4315|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nTributes to Henry Dalziel VC include:\n# Dalziel Street in Nundah, an inner suburb of Brisbane, was named after him in about 1948.\n# Dalziel Avenue in Atherton, Queensland bares his namesake.\n# Henry Dalziel Oval at Irvinebank, Queensland is named in his honour.\n# There is a memorial to Henry at Loudon House Museum at Irvinebank.\n# The bar at the Atherton, Queensland, Returned Servicemen's Club is called The Harry Dalziel VC Memorial Bar.\n# In a park in Atherton a mounted WWI artillery piece stands as a memorial to Private Harry Dalziel VC.\n# The Army barracks at Enoggera (Queensland) and Singleton (NSW) both have roads named in his honour.\n# The officers' club at the Army's [[Enoggera Barracks]] is named 'The Henry Dalziel VC Club'.\n# The Henry Dalziel VC Dialysis Centre, Greenslopes Private Hospital, Greenslopes, Queensland opened and named in his honour on 28 August 2003 by the Hon Danna Vale MP, Minister for Veterans Affairs and Minister Assisting the Minister for Defence. She said,\n<blockquote>\n''\"The brave actions of Henry Dalziel are typical of the Australian spirit that burned brightly in World War I. It helped us to define ourselves as a nation. It gave us values and traditions that today echo and shine in the present generation of Australian servicemen and women. His bravery in the face of the enemy and his refusal to leave his mates despite being wounded are the actions that make his story so special. He was a true Anzac. He never gave up and he always looked after his mates.\"''<ref name=Noble/>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Notes==\n;Footnotes\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |last=Chataway |first=Thomas |title=History of the 15th Battalion 1914\u20131918 |year=1948 |editor=Goldenstedt, Paul |publisher=William Brooks & Co |location=Fortitude Valley, Queensland |oclc=35124181 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |last=Laffin |first=John |authorlink=John Laffin|title=The Battle of Hamel: The Australians' Finest Victory |year=1999 |publisher=Kangaroo Press |location=East Roseville, New South Wales |isbn=0-86417-970-7 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Mays|first1=Helen|chapter=Dalziel, Henry (1893\u20131965)|chapter-url=http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A080224b.htm|title=Australian Dictionary of Biography|volume=Volume 8|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|year=1981|pp=|isbn=|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=They Dared Mightily|editor-first=Lionel|editor-last=Wigmore|year=1963|publisher=Australian War Memorial|edition=|location=Canberra|isbn=|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline|Henry Dalziel}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dalziel, Henry}}\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:Australian farmers]]\n[[Category:Australian gold prospectors]]\n[[Category:Australian military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Australian songwriters]]\n[[Category:Australian World War I recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n[[Category:People from Far North Queensland]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Australian recipient of the Victoria Cross|the British newspaper proprietor and politician|Henry Dalziel, 1st Baron Dalziel of Kirkcaldy}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name              = Henry Dalziel\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| image         = File:StateLibQld 2 93480 Private Henry Dalziel, V.C.jpg\n| image_size    = 175\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Private Henry Dalziel, c.1919\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=y|1893|2|18}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|1965|7|24|1893|2|18}}\n| birth_place   = [[Irvinebank]], Queensland\n| death_place   = Greenslopes Repatriation Hospital, [[Brisbane]], Queensland\n| placeofburial = [[Mt Thompson Crematorium]]\n| nickname      =\n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance    = Australia\n| branch        = [[Australian Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1915\u201319<br/>1933\u201343\n| rank          = [[Sergeant]]\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = [[15th Battalion (Australia)|15th Battalion (Queensland & Tasmania)]]\n| commands      = \n| battles       = First World War\n* [[Battle of Hamel]]\n* [[Battle of the Somme]]\n* [[Battle of Pozi\u00e8res]]\n* [[Battle of Mouquet Farm]]\n* [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]]\n* [[Battle of Passchendaele]]\n| awards        = [[Victoria Cross]]\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n}}\n'''Henry Dalziel''', [[Victoria Cross|VC]] (18 February 1893 \u2013 24 July 1965) was an [[List of Australian Victoria Cross recipients|Australian recipient]] of the [[Victoria Cross]] (VC), the highest award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to British and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] forces. He was awarded the VC while serving with the [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] during the [[First World War]]. Dalziel's VC was the 1,000th awarded. After the war, Dalziel returned to Australia and tried to make a living by farming. Troubled by the injuries he sustained during the war, he left the land and took up factory work. He moved between jobs several times during the 1930s, and led something of a transient lifestyle, even at one stage turning to gold prospecting. In the mid-1930s he rejoined the army in a part-time capacity and during the [[Second World War]] served in a training role in Australia. He died in 1965 at the age of 72.\n\n==Early life==\nHenry Dalziel, the son of a [[Queensland]] miner, was born on 18 February 1893 in [[Irvinebank]]. After completing his education he began working as a fireman on the railway.{{sfn|Mays|1981|pp=202\u2013203}}\n\n==First World War==\nDalziel volunteered for the [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] (AIF) in early 1915 and was posted to the [[15th Battalion (Australia)|15th Battalion]] as a reinforcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://discoveringanzacs.naa.gov.au/browse/person/141440 |title=Henry Dalziel \u2013 Discovering Anzacs |publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]] |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> He served throughout the [[Gallipoli Campaign]] until he was evacuated, along with the rest of his battalion, to Egypt in December 1915. From July 1916, he served on the [[Western Front (WWI)|Western Front]] in France and fought in the [[Battle of the Somme|Battles of the Somme]], [[Battle of Pozi\u00e8res|Pozi\u00e8res]] and [[Battle of Mouquet Farm|Mouquet Farm]]. His service continued into 1917, including the [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]] but he was wounded during the [[Battle of Passchendaele]] at [[Battle of Polygon Wood|Polygon Wood]]. He returned to the front in June 1918.{{sfn|Mays|1981|pp=202\u2013203}}\n\n[[File:Private Henry (Harry) Dalziel, awarded Victoria Cross.jpg|thumb|Private Henry Dalziel in England circa 1918, wearing a bandage under his hat]]\nIt was during the [[Battle of Hamel]] that Dalziel performed the deed for which he was awarded the Victoria Cross (VC). Assigned to the battalion's transport company as a driver, he volunteered to join the attack to make up for a manpower shortage that the battalion was experiencing at that time.{{sfn|Chataway|1948|pp=213\u2013214}} On 4 July 1918 at [[Hamel Wood]], when determined resistance was coming from an enemy strong-point which was also protected by strong wire entanglements, Dalziel, armed only with a revolver, attacked an enemy machine-gun. He killed or captured the entire crew and, although severely wounded in the hand, carried on until the final objective was captured. He twice went over open ground under heavy artillery and machine-gun fire to obtain ammunition and, although suffering from loss of blood, continued to fill magazines and serve his gun until wounded in the head.{{sfn|Laffin|1999|pp=77\u201378}}{{refn|Dalziel's personal account of the action was as follows: \"We were harassed by murderous fire from a nearby enemy stronghold, the Australian advance was held up. My gun had cleaned up one [machinegun] nest, but another planted in a different direction opened fire. I dashed at it killing seven Germans with my two revolvers. One German bloodhound wounded me in the hand, but I soon had him on the ground. I lunged at him with my German dagger, catching him right over the heart. His dying cry upset me and I shivered.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Barlass|first=Tim|title=World War I VC to go up for auction|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/world-war-i-vc-to-go-up-for-auction-20101113-17rul.html|journal=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=14 November 2010|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>|group=Note}} The citation for his VC, published in the ''[[London Gazette]]'', read:\n\n{{Quote|For most conspicuous bravery and devotion to duty when in action with a [[Lewis gun]] section. His company met with determined resistance from a strong point which was strongly garrisoned, manned by numerous machine-guns and, undamaged by our [[artillery]] fire, was also protected by strong wire entanglements. A heavy concentration of machine-gun fire caused many casualties, and held up our advance. His Lewis gun having come into action and silenced enemy guns in one direction, an enemy gun opened fire from another direction. Private Dalziel dashed at it and with his [[revolver]], killed or captured the entire crew and gun, and allowed our advance to continue. He was severely wounded in the hand, but carried on and took part in the capture of the final objective. He twice went over open ground under heavy enemy artillery and machine-gun fire to secure ammunition, and though suffering from considerable loss of blood, he filled magazines and served his gun until severely wounded through the head. His magnificent bravery and devotion to duty was an inspiring example to all his comrades and his dash and unselfish courage at a critical time undoubtedly saved many lives and turned what would have been a serious check into a splendid success.|The London Gazette, 17 August 1918<ref name='LonGaz'>{{London Gazette |issue=30849 |date=17 August 1918 |pages=9660\u20139660  |supp=y |city=l }}</ref>}}\n\nDalziel's VC was the 1,000th such medal to be awarded.{{sfn|Wigmore|1963|pp=129\u2013130}} His wounds were so severe that his brain was exposed and he was evacuated to England for medical treatment. It was not until January 1919 that he returned to Australia.{{sfn|Mays|1981|pp=202\u2013203}}\n\n==Later life==\nDischarged from the AIF in July 1919,{{sfn|Wigmore|1963|pp=129\u2013130}} the following year he married Ida Maude Ramsay, who had served as a nurse with the 17th Australian General Hospital. The couple took up a block of land for farming but his wife was primarily responsible for its running. After a few years, Dalziel tired of farming and moved to Sydney where he took up factory work. His wife remained on the farm.{{sfn|Mays|1981|pp=202\u2013203}} He then tried his hand at gold mining in the [[Bathurst, New South Wales|Bathurst region]] before later returning to the farm when his wife became ill.{{sfn|Wigmore|1963|pp=129\u2013130}} By 1933, he was living in [[Brisbane]] but out of work.{{sfn|Mays|1981|pp=202\u2013203}} At this time, having maintained an interest in song writing since his time in hospital recuperating from his war wounds, he had some of his work published in England and the United States.{{sfn|Wigmore|1963|pp=129\u2013130}}\n\nFrom 1933, Dalziel served in the [[Australian Army Reserve|Citizen Military Forces]] and was a sergeant in the 9th/15th Battalion.  During the Second World War, he did not serve abroad. Instead he supported recruitment and funding drives. He also conducted talks for troops at training camps. His final posting before he was discharged from the Army in December 1943 was to the 11th Training Battalion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ww2roll.gov.au/Veteran.aspx?ServiceId=A&VeteranId=102074 |title=Dalziel, Henry |work=World War II Nominal Roll |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia |accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> In 1956, he travelled to England for the VC centenary celebrations.<ref name=Willey>{{cite web|last1=Willey|first1=Harry|title=Private Harry Dalziel|url=http://www.firstworldwar.com/features/dalziel.htm|publisher=firstworldwar.com|accessdate=12 September 2014}}</ref> In late life, Dalziel lived in [[Oxley, Queensland|Oxley]].{{sfn|Wigmore|1963|pp=129\u2013130}}\n\nOn 24 July 1965, Dalziel suffered a stroke and died at the [[Greenslopes Private Hospital]] in Brisbane. He was cremated with full military honours. A plaque in his memory is laid at [[Mount Thompson crematorium]], Brisbane.<ref name=Willey/>\n\n==Legacy==\nOn 25 November 2010, a group of Dalziel's medals and associated documents were auctioned by Noble Numismatics in Sydney, fetching AUD $525,000 + commission.<ref name=Noble>{{cite web|url=http://www.noble.com.au/auctions/lot?id=263759|title = Lot 4315|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nTributes to Henry Dalziel VC include:\n# Dalziel Street in Nundah, an inner suburb of Brisbane, was named after him in about 1948.\n# Dalziel Avenue in Atherton, Queensland bares his namesake.\n# Henry Dalziel Oval at Irvinebank, Queensland is named in his honour.\n# There is a memorial to Henry at Loudon House Museum at Irvinebank.\n# The bar at the Atherton, Queensland, Returned Servicemen's Club is called The Harry Dalziel VC Memorial Bar.\n# In a park in Atherton a mounted WWI artillery piece stands as a memorial to Private Harry Dalziel VC.\n# The Army barracks at Enoggera (Queensland) and Singleton (NSW) both have roads named in his honour.\n# The officers' club at the Army's [[Enoggera Barracks]] is named 'The Henry Dalziel VC Club'.\n# The Henry Dalziel VC Dialysis Centre, Greenslopes Private Hospital, Greenslopes, Queensland opened and named in his honour on 28 August 2003 by the Hon Danna Vale MP, Minister for Veterans Affairs and Minister Assisting the Minister for Defence. She said,\n<blockquote>\n''\"The brave actions of Henry Dalziel are typical of the Australian spirit that burned brightly in World War I. It helped us to define ourselves as a nation. It gave us values and traditions that today echo and shine in the present generation of Australian servicemen and women. His bravery in the face of the enemy and his refusal to leave his mates despite being wounded are the actions that make his story so special. He was a true Anzac. He never gave up and he always looked after his mates.\"''<ref name=Noble/>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Notes==\n;Footnotes\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |last=Chataway |first=Thomas |title=History of the 15th Battalion 1914\u20131918 |year=1948 |editor=Goldenstedt, Paul |publisher=William Brooks & Co |location=Fortitude Valley, Queensland |oclc=35124181 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |last=Laffin |first=John |authorlink=John Laffin|title=The Battle of Hamel: The Australians' Finest Victory |year=1999 |publisher=Kangaroo Press |location=East Roseville, New South Wales |isbn=0-86417-970-7 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Mays|first1=Helen|chapter=Dalziel, Henry (1893\u20131965)|chapter-url=http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A080224b.htm|title=Australian Dictionary of Biography|volume=Volume 8|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|year=1981|pp=|isbn=|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=They Dared Mightily|editor-first=Lionel|editor-last=Wigmore|year=1963|publisher=Australian War Memorial|edition=|location=Canberra|isbn=|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline|Henry Dalziel}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dalziel, Henry}}\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:Australian farmers]]\n[[Category:Australian gold prospectors]]\n[[Category:Australian military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Australian songwriters]]\n[[Category:Australian World War I recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n[[Category:People from Far North Queensland]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater life:replaced: moved to Sydney \u2192 moved to Sydney,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Dalziel"}
{"title_page": "Alexander Hugh Chisholm", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2016}}\n'''Alexander Hugh Chisholm''' [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] [[Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales|FRZS]] (28 March 1890 \u2014 10 July 1977) also known as '''Alec Chisholm''', was a noted Australian naturalist, [[journalist]], [[editing|newspaper editor]], [[author]] and [[ornithologist]].  He was a member of the [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]] (RAOU), President of the RAOU 1939\u20131940, and editor of its journal the ''[[Emu (journal)|Emu]]'' from 1926 to 1928.  In 1941 he was elected a [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union Fellows|Fellow of the RAOU]] in 1941 and the previous year he had been the first recipient of the [[Australian Natural History Medallion]] for his work in ornithology and popularising natural history. Chisholm was a prolific and popular writer of articles and books, mainly on birds and nature but also on history, literature and biography.<ref>{{Cite book|title=IDLING IN GREEN PLACES : a life of alec chisholm.|last=MCGREGOR, RUSSELL.|date=2019|publisher=AUSTRALIAN SCHOLARLY PUB|isbn=978-1-925801-99-6|oclc=1119561712}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.environmentandsociety.org/arcadia/mateship-birds-australian-plea-conservation-0|title=Mateship with Birds: An Australian Plea for Conservation {{!}} Environment & Society Portal|website=www.environmentandsociety.org|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> He is not to be confused with his near-contemporary the anti-semite and enthusiast of Germany's [[Nazism|National Socialists]], the Melbourne University linguist Alan R. Chisholm.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Bird, David S. (David Samuel.) | title=Nazi dreamtime : Australian enthusiasts for Hitler's Germany | publication-date=2012 | publisher=Australian Scholarly | isbn=978-1-921875-42-7 }}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nAlec H. Chisholm was born on 28 March 1890 at [[Maryborough, Victoria|Maryborough]], Victoria, seventh of eight children. His father was Colin Chisholm, an Australian-born grocer, and his wife Charlotte, n\u00e9e Kennedy, from Scotland.<ref>Tess Kloot, 'Chisholm, Alexander Hugh (Alec) (1890\u20131977)', Australian Dictionary of Biography, Volume 13, (MUP), 1993</ref> He was educated at Maryborough State School until the age of 12.\n\n== Conservationist ==\nBy the time he began work as a journalist, Chisholm already had a name as a conservationist. In 1907, aged seventeen, he joined the [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]] and during the next year wrote six articles in the organisation's journal, the ''[[Emu (journal)|Emu]]''. In the ''Maryborough and Dunolly Advertiser'' he campaigned in 1908 against the killing of [[Egret|egrets]] for feathers for women's hats, a crusade in which he won support from Australian poet [[Mary Gilmore|Dame Mary Gilmore]]. In 1911 he was employed at the newspaper as a journalist, leaving in 1915 for a position at the ''Brisbane Mail''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eoas.info/biogs/P001137b.htm|title=Chisholm, Alexander Hugh (Alec) (1890 - 1977)|website=Encyclopedia of Australian Science|publisher=University of Melbourne eScholarship Research Centre|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Kloot|first=Tess|title=Chisholm, Alexander Hugh (Alec) (1890\u20131977)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/chisholm-alexander-hugh-alec-9741|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> He continued to campaign for the conservation of Australia's birds, animals and plants for the rest of his life.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The flight of the emu : a hundred years of Australian ornithology, 1901-2001|last=Robin, Libby, 1956-|date=2001|publisher=Melbourne University Press|isbn=0-522-84987-3|oclc=49001691}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nOn 8 November 1923 Chisholm married Olive May Haseler in Brisbane.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article20675427|title=PRE-WEDDING DINNER.|date=7 November 1923|newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]]|accessdate=6 March 2018|issue=20,528|location=Queensland, Australia|page=18|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> They had one daughter,  Deirdre, who was born on 26 December 1924. From 1964, Olive Chisholm's health deteriorated seriously. Alec cared for her as best he could until late 1968, when she was committed to Balmoral Hill Convalescent Home, where she died in 1970. By this time, his own health was in serious decline, although he continued living alone in a small flat in Sydney's Cremorne Point until his death in 1977.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGill|first=A. R.|date=1977-10-01|title=Alexander Hugh Chisholm|journal=Emu - Austral Ornithology|volume=77|issue=4|pages=232\u2013235|doi=10.1071/MU9770232|issn=0158-4197}}</ref>\n\n== Journalist and editor ==\nChisholm worked as a journalist in Queensland from 1915 to 1922, then moved to Sydney, where he became news editor of the ''Daily Telegraph'' and later editor of the ''Sunday Pictorial''. After moving to Melbourne in 1933, he was for many years editor of the ''Australasian'', before being appointed editor of [[The Argus (Melbourne)|''The Argus'']] in June 1937.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article74199326|title=Editor Of Melbourne \"Argus\" Retires|date=30 June 1937|newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]]|accessdate=6 March 2018|location=South Australia|page=22|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article25409635|title=\"ARGUS\" CHANGES|date=30 June 1937|newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]]|accessdate=6 March 2018|issue=20,780|location=Tasmania, Australia|volume=CXLVI|page=9|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  He spent ten years, from 1948 to 1958, editing the ten-volume ''[[Australian Encyclopaedia]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/10070570 |title=Chisholm, Alec H. (Alec Hugh), 1890-1977 |website=Trove |publisher=National Library of Australia |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> for which he was awarded the [[Order of the British Empire]]. Chisholm was also editor of ''[[The Victorian Naturalist]]'' and ''[[Who's Who in Australia]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/11328795|title=Who's who in Australia: (incorporating Johns's notable Australians / compiled and edited by Alec H. Chisholm|website=Trove|publisher=National Library of Australia|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> In his late years he wrote several entries on ornithologists, naturalists and explorers in the [[Australian Dictionary of Biography|''Australian Dictionary of Biography'']]. He was a contributor of articles to a number of publications, including ''[[Walkabout (magazine)|Walkabout]]'', the latter mostly on Australian bird life and history.\n\n== Historian ==\nVisiting England in 1938, Chisholm discovered a large number of documents relating to the nineteenth-century ornithologist [[John Gould]]. They included the diary kept by Gould's principal collector, [[John Gilbert (naturalist)|John Gilbert]], during his participation in [[Ludwig Leichhardt]]\u2019s 1844-45 expedition to [[Port Essington]]. This diary became the foundation of Chisholm's 1941 book, ''Strange New World''. He published several later works of history, but none achieved the popularity or notoriety of his Gilbert and Leichhardt book.<ref>{{Cite book|title=IDLING IN GREEN PLACES : a life of alec chisholm.|last=MCGREGOR, RUSSELL.|date=2019|publisher=AUSTRALIAN SCHOLARLY PUB|isbn=978-1-925801-99-6|oclc=1119561712}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and offices==\n* 1918\u20131922 \u2013 adviser and lecturer on natural history for the Queensland Government\n* 1919\u20131922 \u2013 president, Queensland Gould League of Bird Lovers\n* 1920\u20131922 \u2013 president, Queensland Naturalists' Club\n* 1920\u20131922 \u2013 editor, ''Queensland Naturalist''\n* 1922 \u2013 corresponding fellow, [[American Ornithologists' Union]]\n* 1926\u20131928 \u2013 editor, ''[[Emu (journal)|Emu]]''\n* 1934 \u2013 president, [[Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales]]\n* 1937\u20131938 \u2013 president, Victorian Bird Observers' Club\n* 1937\u20131938 \u2013 president, [[Field Naturalists Club of Victoria]]\n* 1939\u20131940 \u2013 president, [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]]\n* 1939\u20131948 \u2013 editor, ''[[The Victorian Naturalist]]''\n* 1940 \u2013 Australian Natural History Medallion (Field Naturalists Club of Victoria)\n* 1940 \u2013 inaugural recipient of the [[Australian Natural History Medallion]]\n* [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]]\n* Fellow of the Royal Zoological Society\n* Fellow of the [[Royal Australian Historical Society]]\n* Fellow of the [[Royal Historical Society of Queensland]]\n* Member of the [[British Ornithologists' Union]]\n\n==Books==\n\n* Chisholm, A. H., ''The Story of Elizabeth Gould'' (Melbourne: Hawthorn Press, 1944).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Strange New World: The Adventures of John Gilbert and Ludwig Leichardt'' (Sydney: Angus & Robertson, 1955).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Ferdinand von Mueller'' (Melbourne: Oxford University Press, 1962).\n*\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Mateship with Birds''. [[Whitcombe & Tombs Ltd]]: Melbourne.(1922)\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Birds and Green Places. A book of Australian nature gossip''. J.M. Dent & Sons Ltd: London.(1929)\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Nature Fantasy in Australia''. J.M. Dent & Sons Ltd: London.(1932).\n*\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Bird Wonders of Australia''. Angus & Robertson: Sydney. This book went through six editions, the last being issued in 1969.(1934).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''An Explorer and His Birds. [[John Gilbert (naturalist)|John Gilbert]]'s discoveries in 1844-45''. Brown, Prior, Anderson: Mebourne.(1945).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''The Making of a Sentimental Bloke : A sketch of the remarkable career of C.J. Dennis'', Georgian house: Melbourne.(1946).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Fairy Wrens''. F.W. Cheshire Pty Ltd: Melbourne.(1948).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''News from Nature. A selection of seasonal gossip''. Georgian House: Melbourne.(1948).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Scots Wha Hae : History of the Royal Caledonian Society of Melbourne'', Angus & Robertson: Sydney. (1950).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''The Romance of the Lyrebird''. Angus & Robertson Pty Ltd: Sydney.(1960).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''The Joy of the Earth''. Collins: Sydney.(1969).\n\n==Book sections==\n* Chisholm, A. H., [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A010407b.htm \"Gilbert, John (1810?\u20131845)\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), pp. 441\u2013442.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A010084b.htm \"Bennett, George (1804\u20131893), medical practitioner and naturalist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), pp. 85\u201386.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Gilbert, John (1810?\u20131845), naturalist and explorer\" in ''Journal of the Royal Australian Historical Society'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), pp. 441\u2013442.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A010426b.htm \"Gould, Elizabeth (1804\u20131841), natural history artist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), p. 465.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A010427b.htm \"Gould, John (1804\u20131881), zoologist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), pp. 465\u2013467.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A030453b.htm \"Coxen, Charles (1809\u20131876), naturalist and politician\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 3 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1969), pp. 487\u2013488.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A030308b.htm \"Calvert, James Snowden (1825\u20131884), explorer and botanist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 3 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1969), p. 333.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A030223b.htm \"Broinowski, Gracius Joseph (1837\u20131913), artist and ornithologist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 3 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1969), p. 239.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A030060b.htm \"Atkinson, Caroline Louisa Waring (1834\u20131872), naturalist and writer\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 3 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1969), pp. 59\u201360.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A040423b.htm \"Helms, Richard (1842\u20131914), zoologist and botanist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 4 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1972), p. 374.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A040141b.htm \"Elsey, Joseph Ravenscroft (1834\u20131857), surgeon, explorer and naturalist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 4 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1972), p. 139.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A060004b.htm \"Ramsay, Edward Pierson (1842\u20131916), ornithologist and zoologist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Bede Nairn, ed., vol. 6 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1976), pp. 3\u20134.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A060411b.htm \"Wheelwright, Horace (Horatio) William (1815\u20131865)\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Bede Nairn, ed., vol. 6 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1976), pp. 383\u2013384.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A070191b.htm \"Barrett, Charles Leslie (1879\u20131959), naturalist and journalist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Bede Nairn and Geoffrey Serle, eds, vol. 7 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1979), p. 185.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A070605b.htm \"Cayley, Neville William (1886\u20131950), ornithologist and artist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Bede Nairn and Geoffrey Serle, eds, vol. 7 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1979), pp. 596\u2013597.\n* Kloot, Tess, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A130463b.htm \"Chisholm, Alexander Hugh (1890\u20131977), Journalist, Ornithologist and Encyclopaedist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', John Ritchie, ed., vol. 13 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1993), pp. 422\u2013423.\n\n==Edited books==\n* Chisholm, A. H. ed., ''Journal of a Voyage to New South Wales with Sixty-five Plates of New Descript Animals, Birds, Lizards, Serpents, Curious Cones of Trees and other Natural Productions'' by John White, Esq. (Sydney: Angus & Robertson for Royal Australian Historical Society, 1962).\n\n==Journal articles==\n* Balmford, Peter, \"Newspapers as a Source of Information about Natural History\", ''Victorian Naturalist'', 102 (1) (1985), 20\u201327.\n* Chisholm, A. H., \"The Ornithological History of Queensland\", ''Queensland Naturalist'', lii (1922), 66\u201379; 93\u2013101; 115\u2013123.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Some Letters from George Grey to John Gould\", ''Emu'', 38 (1938).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"John Gilbert. Some Letters to Gould\", ''Emu'', 38 (1938).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"The Story of John Gilbert.\", ''Emu'', 39 (1940), 156\u2013176.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Mrs John Gould and her Relations\", ''Emu'' (1941).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"John Gould's Australian Prospectus\", ''Emu'', 42 (1942), 74\u201384.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Birds of the Gilbert Diary\", ''Emu'', 44 (1944), 131\u2013150.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"An Explorer and His Birds. John Gilbert\"s Discoveries in 1844\u20135\" (1945).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"The Diaries of S. W. Jackson\", ''Emu'', 58 (1958), 75\u201376.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"J. R. Elsey, Surgeon, Naturalist, Explorer\", ''Queensland Naturalist'', 17 (3/4) (1964), 60\u201370.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Some Early Letters in Australian Ornithology\", ''Emu'', 63 (1964).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"J. R. Elsey, Explorer of the Never-Never\", ''Journal of the Royal Australian Historical Society'', 52 (1966).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Dudley Dickison - Student of Birds and Books\", ''Victorian Naturalist'', 84 (8) (1967), 251\u2013253.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Obituary. Gilbert Roscoe Gannon\", ''Proceedings of the Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales'', 89 (1968), 12.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Obituaries: Roy Percy Cooper\", ''Emu'', 77 (2) (1977), 88.\n==Journal articles about Alexander Chisholm==\n* McGill, A. R., \"Alexander Hugh Chisholm\", ''Emu'', 77 (1977), 232\u2013235.\n* Willis, J. H., \"Alexander Hugh Chisholm, OBE, CMZS., C.F.A.O.U. (1890\u20131977). An Appreciation\", ''Victorian Naturalist'', 94 (5) (1977), 188\u2013190.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Alec H. Chisholm in the [http://www.eoas.info/biogs/P001137b.htm ''Encyclopaedia of Australian Science'']\n* Biography in [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/chisholm-alexander-hugh-alec-9741 ''The Australian Dictionary of Biography'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chisholm, Alexander Hugh}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Australian editors]]\n[[Category:Australian encyclopedists]]\n[[Category:Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Australian naturalists]]\n[[Category:Australian nature writers]]\n[[Category:Australian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Australian ornithologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2016}}\n'''Alexander Hugh Chisholm''' [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] [[Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales|FRZS]] (28 March 1890 \u2014 10 July 1977) also known as '''Alec Chisholm''', was a noted Australian naturalist, [[journalist]], [[editing|newspaper editor]], [[author]] and [[ornithologist]].  He was a member of the [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]] (RAOU), President of the RAOU 1939\u20131940, and editor of its journal the ''[[Emu (journal)|Emu]]'' from 1926 to 1928.  In 1941 he was elected a [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union Fellows|Fellow of the RAOU]] in 1941 and the previous year he had been the first recipient of the [[Australian Natural History Medallion]] for his work in ornithology and popularising natural history. Chisholm was a prolific and popular writer of articles and books, mainly on birds and nature but also on history, literature and biography.<ref>{{Cite book|title=IDLING IN GREEN PLACES : a life of alec chisholm.|last=MCGREGOR, RUSSELL.|date=2019|publisher=AUSTRALIAN SCHOLARLY PUB|isbn=978-1-925801-99-6|oclc=1119561712}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.environmentandsociety.org/arcadia/mateship-birds-australian-plea-conservation-0|title=Mateship with Birds: An Australian Plea for Conservation {{!}} Environment & Society Portal|website=www.environmentandsociety.org|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> He is not to be confused with his near-contemporary the anti-semite and enthusiast of Germany's [[Nazism|National Socialists]], the Melbourne University linguist Alan R. Chisholm.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Bird, David S. (David Samuel.) | title=Nazi dreamtime : Australian enthusiasts for Hitler's Germany | publication-date=2012 | publisher=Australian Scholarly | isbn=978-1-921875-42-7 }}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nAlec H. Chisholm was born on 28 March 1890 at [[Maryborough, Victoria|Maryborough]], Victoria, seventh of eight children. His father was Colin Chisholm, an Australian-born grocer, and his wife Charlotte, n\u00e9e Kennedy, from Scotland.<ref>Tess Kloot, 'Chisholm, Alexander Hugh (Alec) (1890\u20131977)', Australian Dictionary of Biography, Volume 13, (MUP), 1993</ref> He was educated at Maryborough State School until the age of 12.\n\n== Conservationist ==\nBy the time he began work as a journalist, Chisholm already had a name as a conservationist. In 1907, aged seventeen, he joined the [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]] and during the next year wrote six articles in the organisation's journal, the ''[[Emu (journal)|Emu]]''. In the ''Maryborough and Dunolly Advertiser'' he campaigned in 1908 against the killing of [[Egret|egrets]] for feathers for women's hats, a crusade in which he won support from Australian poet [[Mary Gilmore|Dame Mary Gilmore]]. In 1911 he was employed at the newspaper as a journalist, leaving in 1915 for a position at the ''Brisbane Mail''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eoas.info/biogs/P001137b.htm|title=Chisholm, Alexander Hugh (Alec) (1890 - 1977)|website=Encyclopedia of Australian Science|publisher=University of Melbourne eScholarship Research Centre|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Kloot|first=Tess|title=Chisholm, Alexander Hugh (Alec) (1890\u20131977)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/chisholm-alexander-hugh-alec-9741|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> He continued to campaign for the conservation of Australia's birds, animals and plants for the rest of his life.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The flight of the emu : a hundred years of Australian ornithology, 1901-2001|last=Robin, Libby, 1956-|date=2001|publisher=Melbourne University Press|isbn=0-522-84987-3|oclc=49001691}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nOn 8 November 1923 Chisholm married Olive May Haseler in Brisbane.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article20675427|title=PRE-WEDDING DINNER.|date=7 November 1923|newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]]|accessdate=6 March 2018|issue=20,528|location=Queensland, Australia|page=18|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> They had one daughter,  Deirdre, who was born on 26 December 1924. From 1964, Olive Chisholm's health deteriorated seriously. Alec cared for her as best he could until late 1968, when she was committed to Balmoral Hill Convalescent Home, where she died in 1970. By this time, his own health was in serious decline, although he continued living alone in a small flat in Sydney's Cremorne Point until his death in 1977.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGill|first=A. R.|date=1977-10-01|title=Alexander Hugh Chisholm|journal=Emu - Austral Ornithology|volume=77|issue=4|pages=232\u2013235|doi=10.1071/MU9770232|issn=0158-4197}}</ref>\n\n== Journalist and editor ==\nChisholm worked as a journalist in Queensland from 1915 to 1922, then moved to Sydney where he became news editor of the ''Daily Telegraph'' and later editor of the ''Sunday Pictorial''. After moving to Melbourne in 1933, he was for many years editor of the ''Australasian'', before being appointed editor of [[The Argus (Melbourne)|''The Argus'']] in June 1937.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article74199326|title=Editor Of Melbourne \"Argus\" Retires|date=30 June 1937|newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]]|accessdate=6 March 2018|location=South Australia|page=22|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article25409635|title=\"ARGUS\" CHANGES|date=30 June 1937|newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]]|accessdate=6 March 2018|issue=20,780|location=Tasmania, Australia|volume=CXLVI|page=9|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  He spent ten years, from 1948 to 1958, editing the ten-volume ''[[Australian Encyclopaedia]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/10070570 |title=Chisholm, Alec H. (Alec Hugh), 1890-1977 |website=Trove |publisher=National Library of Australia |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> for which he was awarded the [[Order of the British Empire]]. Chisholm was also editor of ''[[The Victorian Naturalist]]'' and ''[[Who's Who in Australia]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/11328795|title=Who's who in Australia: (incorporating Johns's notable Australians / compiled and edited by Alec H. Chisholm|website=Trove|publisher=National Library of Australia|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> In his late years he wrote several entries on ornithologists, naturalists and explorers in the [[Australian Dictionary of Biography|''Australian Dictionary of Biography'']]. He was a contributor of articles to a number of publications, including ''[[Walkabout (magazine)|Walkabout]]'', the latter mostly on Australian bird life and history.\n\n== Historian ==\nVisiting England in 1938, Chisholm discovered a large number of documents relating to the nineteenth-century ornithologist [[John Gould]]. They included the diary kept by Gould's principal collector, [[John Gilbert (naturalist)|John Gilbert]], during his participation in [[Ludwig Leichhardt]]\u2019s 1844-45 expedition to [[Port Essington]]. This diary became the foundation of Chisholm's 1941 book, ''Strange New World''. He published several later works of history, but none achieved the popularity or notoriety of his Gilbert and Leichhardt book.<ref>{{Cite book|title=IDLING IN GREEN PLACES : a life of alec chisholm.|last=MCGREGOR, RUSSELL.|date=2019|publisher=AUSTRALIAN SCHOLARLY PUB|isbn=978-1-925801-99-6|oclc=1119561712}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and offices==\n* 1918\u20131922 \u2013 adviser and lecturer on natural history for the Queensland Government\n* 1919\u20131922 \u2013 president, Queensland Gould League of Bird Lovers\n* 1920\u20131922 \u2013 president, Queensland Naturalists' Club\n* 1920\u20131922 \u2013 editor, ''Queensland Naturalist''\n* 1922 \u2013 corresponding fellow, [[American Ornithologists' Union]]\n* 1926\u20131928 \u2013 editor, ''[[Emu (journal)|Emu]]''\n* 1934 \u2013 president, [[Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales]]\n* 1937\u20131938 \u2013 president, Victorian Bird Observers' Club\n* 1937\u20131938 \u2013 president, [[Field Naturalists Club of Victoria]]\n* 1939\u20131940 \u2013 president, [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]]\n* 1939\u20131948 \u2013 editor, ''[[The Victorian Naturalist]]''\n* 1940 \u2013 Australian Natural History Medallion (Field Naturalists Club of Victoria)\n* 1940 \u2013 inaugural recipient of the [[Australian Natural History Medallion]]\n* [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]]\n* Fellow of the Royal Zoological Society\n* Fellow of the [[Royal Australian Historical Society]]\n* Fellow of the [[Royal Historical Society of Queensland]]\n* Member of the [[British Ornithologists' Union]]\n\n==Books==\n\n* Chisholm, A. H., ''The Story of Elizabeth Gould'' (Melbourne: Hawthorn Press, 1944).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Strange New World: The Adventures of John Gilbert and Ludwig Leichardt'' (Sydney: Angus & Robertson, 1955).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Ferdinand von Mueller'' (Melbourne: Oxford University Press, 1962).\n*\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Mateship with Birds''. [[Whitcombe & Tombs Ltd]]: Melbourne.(1922)\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Birds and Green Places. A book of Australian nature gossip''. J.M. Dent & Sons Ltd: London.(1929)\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Nature Fantasy in Australia''. J.M. Dent & Sons Ltd: London.(1932).\n*\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Bird Wonders of Australia''. Angus & Robertson: Sydney. This book went through six editions, the last being issued in 1969.(1934).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''An Explorer and His Birds. [[John Gilbert (naturalist)|John Gilbert]]'s discoveries in 1844-45''. Brown, Prior, Anderson: Mebourne.(1945).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''The Making of a Sentimental Bloke : A sketch of the remarkable career of C.J. Dennis'', Georgian house: Melbourne.(1946).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Fairy Wrens''. F.W. Cheshire Pty Ltd: Melbourne.(1948).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''News from Nature. A selection of seasonal gossip''. Georgian House: Melbourne.(1948).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Scots Wha Hae : History of the Royal Caledonian Society of Melbourne'', Angus & Robertson: Sydney. (1950).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''The Romance of the Lyrebird''. Angus & Robertson Pty Ltd: Sydney.(1960).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''The Joy of the Earth''. Collins: Sydney.(1969).\n\n==Book sections==\n* Chisholm, A. H., [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A010407b.htm \"Gilbert, John (1810?\u20131845)\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), pp. 441\u2013442.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A010084b.htm \"Bennett, George (1804\u20131893), medical practitioner and naturalist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), pp. 85\u201386.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Gilbert, John (1810?\u20131845), naturalist and explorer\" in ''Journal of the Royal Australian Historical Society'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), pp. 441\u2013442.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A010426b.htm \"Gould, Elizabeth (1804\u20131841), natural history artist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), p. 465.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A010427b.htm \"Gould, John (1804\u20131881), zoologist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), pp. 465\u2013467.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http: