{"title_page": "Bede people", "text_new": "'''Bede''' or '''Beday''' is a nomadic ethnic group of [[Bangladesh]]. They are also known as '''Manta'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dspace.bracu.ac.bd/xmlui/handle/10361/10295|last=Shejuty|first=Nosin Nahian|title=Identity in flux: a comparative study of Manta and Beday|publisher=BRAC University|date=11 July 2018}}</ref> The Bede traditionally live, travel, and earn their living on the river, which has given them the name of \"Water Gypsy\" or \"River Gypsy.\"<ref name=mobile-school>{{Cite conference|last1=Maksud|first1=A. K. M.|last2=Imtiaj|first2 = R.|title=The Nomadic Bede Community and Their Mobile School Program|booktitle=What Works for the Poorest: Knowledge, Policies and Practices|date=3\u20135 December 2006|url=http://www.bracresearch.org/publications/bede_school.pdf}}</ref> Bede people are similar to [[Romani people|gypsy]] people.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Dalton|first=Edward|title=Tribal History of Eastern India|publisher=Cosmo Publications|location=New Delhi|year=1978}}</ref> They travel in groups and never stay in one place for more than a couple of months.  The majority of the Bedes live on snake related trading, such as [[snake charming]] (training), snake catching, snake selling, etc. They also sell lucky [[Ericaceae|heathers]] and herbal medicines, which they claim have magical properties. Bedes' other occupations are in the entertainment services (e.g. monkey shows, magic shows) and petty trading.<ref name=mobile-school/> Many villagers believe in the magical powers of the gypsies. They can make evil spirits leave someone's body according to magical powers.\n\nSome of them beg on the busy streets of big cities like [[Dhaka]], [[Chittagong]], [[Khulna]]. They do not have any kind of formal education and they do not use medical facilities.  Most of them speak [[Bengali language|Bengali]]. Most of them are Muslim but also practice Hinduism, Shamanism and Animism along with Islam. They are related to other South Asian nomadic groups, such as the [[Domba|Dom]].\n\nThe Bedes are a marginalized group. About 98 percent of Bedes live below the poverty line, and about 95% of Bede children do not attend school. Historically the Bedes were unable to vote as they did not own land, nor could they apply for banks loan or [[microcredit]] for the same reason.<ref name=mobile-school/> However, in 2008 the Bedes were able to win their right to vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2013/01/201312181138776540.html |work=Al Jazeera |publisher=Bijoyeta Das |title=Rough sailing for Bangladesh river-gypsies |url-status=live |accessdate=2 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Dom people}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bede People}}\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Dom in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Romani in Bangladesh]]\n\n{{Asia-ethno-group-stub}}\nman\n", "text_old": "'''Bede''' or '''Beday''' is a nomadic ethnic group of [[Bangladesh]]. They are also known as '''Manta'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dspace.bracu.ac.bd/xmlui/handle/10361/10295|last=Shejuty|first=Nosin Nahian|title=Identity in flux: a comparative study of Manta and Beday|publisher=BRAC University|date=11 July 2018}}</ref> The Bede traditionally live, travel, and earn their living on the river, which has given them the name of \"Water Gypsy\" or \"River Gypsy.\"<ref name=mobile-school>{{Cite conference|last1=Maksud|first1=A. K. M.|last2=Imtiaj|first2 = R.|title=The Nomadic Bede Community and Their Mobile School Program|booktitle=What Works for the Poorest: Knowledge, Policies and Practices|date=3\u20135 December 2006|url=http://www.bracresearch.org/publications/bede_school.pdf}}</ref> Bede people are similar to [[Romani people|gypsy]] people.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Dalton|first=Edward|title=Tribal History of Eastern India|publisher=Cosmo Publications|location=New Delhi|year=1978}}</ref> They travel in groups and never stay in one place for more than a couple of months.  The majority of the Bedes live on snake related trading, such as [[snake charming]] (training), snake catching, snake selling, etc. They also sell lucky [[Ericaceae|heathers]] and herbal medicines, which they claim have magical properties. Bedes' other occupations are in the entertainment services (e.g. monkey shows, magic shows) and petty trading.<ref name=mobile-school/> Many villagers believe in the magical powers of the gypsies. They can make evil spirits leave someone's body according to magical powers.\n\nSome of them beg on the busy streets of big cities like [[Dhaka]], [[Chittagong]], [[Khulna]]. They do not have any kind of formal education and they do not use medical facilities.  Most of them speak [[Bengali language|Bengali]]. Most of them are Muslim but also practice Hinduism, Shamanism and Animism along with Islam. They are related to other South Asian nomadic groups, such as the [[Domba|Dom]].\n\nThe Bedes are a marginalized group. About 98 percent of Bedes live below the poverty line, and about 95% of Bede children do not attend school. Historically the Bedes were unable to vote as they did not own land, nor could they apply for banks loan or [[microcredit]] for the same reason.<ref name=mobile-school/> However, in 2008 the Bedes were able to win their right to vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2013/01/201312181138776540.html |work=Al Jazeera |publisher=Bijoyeta Das |title=Rough sailing for Bangladesh river-gypsies |url-status=live |accessdate=2 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Dom people}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bede People}}\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Dom in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Romani in Bangladesh]]\n\n{{Asia-ethno-group-stub}}\n", "name_user": "103.237.36.230", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReferences)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bede_people"}
{"title_page": "Trimeresurus salazar", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = Trimeresurus_salazar.jpg\n| image_caption = \n| regnum = [[Animalia]]\n| phylum = [[Chordata]]\n| classis = [[Reptilia]]\n| ordo = [[Squamata]]\n| familia = [[Viperidae]]\n| genus = [[Trimeresurus]]\n| species = Salazar\n| binomial = T. salazar\n| subordo = [[Serpentes]]\n| subfamilia = [[Crotalinae]]\n}}\n\n'''Trimeresurus salazar''' is a species of green [[pit viper]] discovered in the lowlands of the western part of [[Arunachal Pradesh]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mirza|first=Zeeshan A.|last2=Bhosale|first2=Harshal S.|last3=Phansalkar|first3=Pushkar U.|last4=Sawant|first4=Mandar|last5=Gowande|first5=Gaurang G.|last6=Patel|first6=Harshil|date=2020-04-15|title=A new species of green pit vipers of the genus Trimeresurus Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de, 1804 (Reptilia, Serpentes, Viperidae) from western Arunachal Pradesh, India|url=https://zse.pensoft.net/article/48431/|journal=Zoosystematics and Evolution|language=en|volume=96(1)|pages=123\u2013138|doi=10.3897/zse.96.48431|issn=1860-0743}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{taxon bar}}\n[[Category:Trimeresurus|salazar]]\n{{Snake-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Taxobox\n| image = Trimeresurus_salazar.jpg\n| image_caption = \n| regnum = [[Animalia]]\n| phylum = [[Chordata]]\n| classis = [[Reptilia]]\n| ordo = [[Squamata]]\n| familia = [[Viperidae]]\n| genus = [[Trimeresurus]]\n| species = Salazar\n| binomial = T. salazar\n| subordo = [[Serpentes]]\n| subfamilia = [[Crotalinae]]\n}}\n\n'''Trimeresurus salazar''' is a species of green [[pit viper]] discovered in the lowlands of the western part of [[Arunachal Pradesh]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mirza|first=Zeeshan A.|last2=Bhosale|first2=Harshal S.|last3=Phansalkar|first3=Pushkar U.|last4=Sawant|first4=Mandar|last5=Gowande|first5=Gaurang G.|last6=Patel|first6=Harshil|date=2020-04-15|title=A new species of green pit vipers of the genus Trimeresurus Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de, 1804 (Reptilia, Serpentes, Viperidae) from western Arunachal Pradesh, India|url=https://zse.pensoft.net/article/48431/|journal=Zoosystematics and Evolution|language=en|volume=96(1)|pages=123\u2013138|doi=10.3897/zse.96.48431|issn=1860-0743}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Species]]\n[[Category:Snakes]]\n[[Category:Viperidae]]\n[[Category:Animals]]\n[[Category:Crotalinae]]\n[[Category:Trimeresurus]]\n[[Category:Chordates]]\n[[Category:Reptiles]]\n[[Category:Squamata]]\n\n{{Snake-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Blythwood", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix categories and indexing, made title italic", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trimeresurus_salazar"}
{"title_page": "Forced conversion to Islam in Pakistan", "text_new": "[[File:Dargah_pir_sarhandi.jpg|thumb|Dargah pir sarhandi, a frequent crime scene of forced conversion and marriage of kidnapped underage Hindu girls.]]\n\nIn [[Pakistan]],boys belonging to the minority [[Hindu]], [[Sikh]], and [[Christianity|Christian]] communities are kidnapped, raped, [[Forced conversion|forcibly converted]] to [[Islam]], and married to [[Muslim]] men.<ref name=aljazeera2014-08-18>{{cite news | url = https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/08/forced-conversions-torment-pakistan-hindus-201481795524630505.html | author = Maham Javaid | title = Forced conversions torment Pakistan's Hindus | work = [[Aljazeera]] | accessdate=27 January 2020 | url-status = live | archivedate = 2014-08-19 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140819234717/https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/08/forced-conversions-torment-pakistan-hindus-201481795524630505.html | quote = According to a report from the Movement for Solidarity and Peace, about 1,000 non-Muslim girls are converted to Islam each year in Pakistan. Every month, an estimated 20 or more Hindu girls are abducted and converted, although exact figures are impossible to gather, said Amarnath Motumal, the vice chairperson of the Human Rights Commission of Pakistan (HRCP).}}</ref> These girls are generally 12 to 18 years old.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia-pacific/new-law-may-help-forced-conversions-pakistani-hindu-girls|title=May Help With Forced Conversions of Pakistani Hindu Girls|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> According to The Centre for Social Justice and Peoples Commission for Minorities\u2019 Rights, a majority of the victims of forced conversion are minor girls as young as 12 years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1548550/forced-conversions|title=Forced conversions|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nEvery year, about 1,000 non-Muslim girls are forcibly converted to Islam in Pakistan.<ref name=thenews2015-07-15>{{Cite news | url = https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/51401-1000-girls-forcibly-converted-to-islam-in-pakistan-every-year | title = 1,000 girls forcibly converted to Islam in Pakistan every year | work = [[The News International|The News]] | date = 2015-07-15 | accessdate=27 January 2020 | url-status = live | archivedate = 2019-09-20 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20190920210516/https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/51401-1000-girls-forcibly-converted-to-islam-in-pakistan-every-year | quote = With the growing intolerance in Pakistani society of religious minorities, evidenced by the increased violence, murder and persecution of religious minorities in the country, forced conversions have emerged as a disturbing trend. }}</ref> The [[United Nations Human Rights Council|Human Rights Council of Pakistan]] has reported that cases of forced conversion are increasing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/51826ef842.html|title=Refworld \u2013 USCIRF Annual Report 2013 \u2013 Countries of Particular Concern: Pakistan|author=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|work=Refworld|date=30 April 2013|accessdate=May 5, 2015|author-link=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217090031/http://www.refworld.org/docid/51826ef842.html|archive-date=17 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada\">{{cite web | url=https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/03/04/PAK104258.E.pdf | title=Pakistan: Religious conversion, including treatment of converts and forced conversions (2009\u20132012) | publisher=Government Research Directorate, [[Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada]] | work=Responses to Information Requests | date= January 14, 2013 | accessdate=January 17, 2018| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504144820/https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/03/04/PAK104258.E.pdf| archivedate=May 4, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to the [[Pakistan Hindu Council]], forced religious conversions are one of the main reasons for migration of Hindus from Pakistan to [[India]].<ref name=usatoday2017-02-15>{{cite news | title = Pakistani Hindus lose daughters to forced Muslim marriages | url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2017/02/15/pakistani-hindus-lose-daughters-forced-muslim-marriages/97013614/ | work = [[USA Today]] | author = Naila Inayat | location = [[Lahore]] | accessdate = 29 January 2020 | url-status = live | archivedate = 2020-01-29 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200129195225/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2017/02/15/pakistani-hindus-lose-daughters-forced-muslim-marriages/97013614/ | quote = The police refused to intervene. Her kidnapper told them she ran away from home, and converted to Islam and married him voluntarily. But after her family pressured a court to intervene, she told judges the truth and they freed her. }}</ref> \n\n[[Sharia|Islamic law]] prohibits forced conversion, following the Quranic principle that there is \"[[Al-Baqara 256|no compulsion in religion]]\" (2:256),<ref name=bonner>{{cite book|author=Michael Bonner|title=Jihad in Islamic History|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2008|pages= 89\u201390|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qxq7eykoJgoC&pg=PA89|quote=To begin with, there was no forced conversion, no choice between \"Islam and the Sword\". Islamic law, following a clear Quranic principle (2:256), prohibited any such things [...] although there have been instances of forced conversion in Islamic history, these have been exceptional.|isbn=978-1400827381}}</ref><ref>Winter, T. J., & Williams, J. A. (2002). ''Understanding Islam and the Muslims: The Muslim Family Islam and World Peace''. Louisville, Kentucky: Fons Vitae. p. 82. {{ISBN|978-1-887752-47-3}}. Quote: The laws of Muslim warfare forbid any forced conversions, and regard them as invalid if they occur.</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|last1 = A.C. Brown|first1 = Jonathan|authorlink = Jonathan A.C. Brown|title = Misquoting Muhammad: The Challenge and Choices of Interpreting the Prophet's Legacy|date = 2014|publisher = [[Oneworld Publications]]|isbn = 978-1-78074-420-9|page = [https://archive.org/details/misquotingmuhamm0000brow/page/92 92]|chapter = 3. The Fragile Truth Of Scripture|quote = 'No compulsion in religion' (2:256) was a Qur'anic command revealed in Medina when a child from one of the Muslim families who had been educated in the town's Jewish schools decided to depart with the Jewish tribe being expelled from Medina. His distraught parents were told by God and the Prophet in this verse that they could not compel their son to stay. The verse, however, has been understood over the centuries as a general command that people cannot be forced to convert to Islam.|chapter-url = https://archive.org/details/misquotingmuhamm0000brow|url = https://archive.org/details/misquotingmuhamm0000brow/page/92}}</ref> but episodes of [[forced conversion]]s are recorded in the [[history of Islam]].\n\nThe majority of reported incidents have taken place in the [[Sindh]] province.{{efn|Sindh is the [[Hinduism in Pakistan#Hindu population by province|only province]] of Pakistan that has a substantial number of Hindus. The Hindus in other provinces constitute small fractions of 1 percent.<ref>[http://www.pbs.gov.pk/sites/default/files/tables/POPULATION%20BY%20RELIGION.pdf Population by religion], Pakistan Bureau of Statstics. Retrieved 3 February 2020. Also reproduced at [https://www.scribd.com/document/400843609/Pakisatn-Bearu-of-Statistics-Population-by-Religion-pdf scribd.com].</ref>}}The [[Sindh]] legislature passed a law in 2016 outlawing forcible conversions and conversions before the age of 18, but the Governor refused to sign it into Act, ostensibly under pressure from Muslim fundamentalist groups. The Sindh province circa 2017 had over seven percent population of Hindus, including [[Dalit]]s.<ref name=\"Atlantic\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/08/hindu-muslim-pakistan/536238/|title=Hindu Today, Muslim Tomorrow|publisher=[[The Atlantic]]|last=Imtiaz|first=Saba|date=14 August 2017|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nReligious institutions like Bharchundi Sharif and Sarhandi Pir support forced conversions and are known to have the support and protection of ruling political parties of Sindh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2020-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107045048/https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/ |archive-date=2020-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to victims\u2019 families and activists, [[Abdul Haq (politician)|Abdul Haq (Mitthu Mian)]] who is a  politician and caretaker of [[Daharki#Religion|Bharachundi Sharif Dargah]] in [[Ghotki district]] and Pir Ayub Jan Sirhindi who is the caretaker of Dargah pir sarhandi in [[Umerkot District]] have supported forced conversions and are known to have the support and protection of the ruling political parties of Sindh.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/|title=Forced conversions of Pakistani Hindu girls|date=19 September 2017|publisher=|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://religionnews.com/2019/06/06/forced-conversions-marriages-spike-in-pakistan/|title=Forced conversions, marriages spike in Pakistan|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191106185952/https://religionnews.com/2019/06/06/forced-conversions-marriages-spike-in-pakistan/|archive-date=2019-11-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the National Commission of Justice and Peace and the [[Pakistan Hindu Council]] (PHC) around 1000 Hindu and Christian minority women are converted to Islam and then forcibly married off to their abductors or rapists. This practice is being reported increasingly in the districts of [[Tharparkar]], [[Umerkot]], and [[Mirpur Khas]] in Sindh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/ |title=Forced conversions of Pakistani Hindu girls - Daily Times |access-date=2020-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107045048/https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/ |archive-date=2020-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> The actual number of cases are estimated to be higher as most of the cases go unreported.<ref>{{cite news|title=Another Hindu temple vandalised in Pakistan, holy books, idols burnt|url=https://www.wionews.com/pakistan/another-hindu-temple-vandalised-in-pakistan-holy-books-idols-burnt-276834|date=2 August 2017|access-date=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127090709/https://www.wionews.com/pakistan/another-hindu-temple-vandalised-in-pakistan-holy-books-idols-burnt-276834|archive-date=27 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the report by the Minority Rights commission, the forced conversions and forced marriages is on the rise in South Punjab, particularly in [[Rahim Yar Khan District|Rahim Yar Khan]] and adjacent areas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/430418/intolerance-growing-in-south-punjab-report/?amp=1|title=Intolerance growing in South Punjab: Report|access-date=8 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020 forced conversions continue in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1548550/forced-conversions  |title=Forced conversions |author=Jahangir, Sulema|date=April 2020|work=Dawn|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Details==\nFirst, underage girls are abducted from their home or where they work, later they re-appear after having been married off to a Muslim. They are often raped and then forcibly converted to Islam. To prevent them from going back home or reporting the rape to the police, the girls are forcibly married to the perpetrators. Reports obtained by the NGO [[Global Human Rights Defence]] indicate that the perpetrators will often put a fake age of the girl on the marriage certificate to hide that she is underage. When the family of the girl tries to report this to the police, they are often met by biased officers who refuse to file an FIR (First Information Report). The conversions are backed by powerful religious instititutions and leaders who also offer incentives to people to convert. Moreover, the perpetrators will often force the victim to sign a report saying that she converted and married out of her own free will, hindering the attempts of the family to have their girl returned to them. Additionally, the perpetrators will often file counter-suits against the victim's family for harassment and for attempting to convert the girl back to her former religion.<ref>{{cite web |title=Human rights report 2019|url=https://ghrdorg.files.wordpress.com/2019/03/report-ghrd-2019.pdf|format=PDF|access-date=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://ghrdorg.files.wordpress.com/2019/03/report-ghrd-2019.pdf|archive-date=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Human rights report 2019|url=https://eptoday.com/files/Religious%20Minorities%20Report.pdf|format=PDF|access-date=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://eptoday.com/files/Religious%20Minorities%20Report.pdf|archive-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to senior journalist Shahzeb Jillani, under-age girls from poor farming communities are especially vulnerable to conversions, he says, \u201cWealthy Muslim farmers see them as fair game for abductions, rape, and prolonged sexual exploitation in captivity. Some notorious religious establishments proudly validate these alleged crimes. State institutions, the police and politicians have encouraged the trend by looking the other way.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/in-pakistan-the-problem-of-forced-conversions/article26823108.ece |title=In Pakistan, the problem of forced conversions|publisher=The Hindu|last=Sarfraz|first=Mehmal|date=13 April 2019|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\nMany people believe that so-called voluntary conversions and marriages are in fact legal cover for the kidnappers, whose young victims fear for their lives and their families\u2019 if they speak the truth publicly.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistan: Hindu Sisters Not Forcibly Converted to Islam |url=https://www.voanews.com/extremism-watch/pakistan-hindu-sisters-not-forcibly-converted-islam |accessdate=13 February 2020 |work=VoA |date=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Human Rights Commission of Pakistan]] found that many girls who had been presumed to have eloped had actually been kidnapped, and were later sold or forced to marry Muslim men. When the young, abducted, Hindu girl who has been forced to convert to Islam appears in court, the fanatics create a great brouhaha and follow her into the building due to which she gets intimidated and is unable to speak<ref name=\"Eloped\">{{cite news |title=Sindh's Stolen Brides |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/sindhs-stolen-brides/229886 |accessdate=14 February 2020 |work=Outlook |date=23 January 2006 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Abdul Hai of the Human Rights Commission of Pakistan, forced conversion of lower caste Hindus is taking place in large numbers but is going unreported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1244684/caste-and-captivity-dalit-suffering-in-sindh|title=Caste and captivity: Dalit suffering in Sindh|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nAccording to the Dalit activist Surendar Valasai, every year around 1,000 to 1,200 Dalit Hindu girls are kidnapped and forcibly converted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1244684/caste-and-captivity-dalit-suffering-in-sindh|title=Caste and captivity: Dalit suffering in Sindh|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nA 2014 report by the Movement for Solidarity and Peace (MSP) says about 1,000 [[women in Pakistan]] are forcibly converted to Islam every year.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anwar|first1=Iqbal|title=1,000 minority girls forced in marriage every year: report|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1098452|website=Dawn|accessdate=25 July 2014|date=2014-04-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140615062301/http://www.dawn.com/news/1098452|archive-date=15 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dunya|first1=Author|title=India ruling party chief urges law against religious conversions|url=http://dunyanews.tv/index.php/en/World/251054-India-ruling-party-chief-urges-law-against-religio|website=[[Dunya News]] |date=20 December 2014|accessdate=20 December 2014|location=New Delhi |agency=[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]]}}</ref> \n\nAccording to Amarnath Motumal, the vice chairperson of the [[Human Rights Commission of Pakistan]], every month, an estimated 20 or more [[Hindu]] girls are abducted and converted, although exact figures are impossible to gather.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/08/forced-conversions-torment-pakistan-hindus-201481795524630505.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2020-01-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629081246/https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/08/forced-conversions-torment-pakistan-hindus-201481795524630505.html |archive-date=2019-06-29 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2014 alone, 265 legal cases of forced conversion were reported mostly involving [[Hindu]] girls.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1170682 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2020-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106221530/https://www.dawn.com/news/1170682 |archive-date=2020-01-06 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the National Commission of Justice and Peace and the [[Pakistan Hindu Council]] (PHC) around 1000 Christian and Hindu minority women are converted to Islam and then forcibly married off to their abductors or rapists. This practice is being reported increasingly in the districts of [[Tharparkar]], [[Umerkot]], and [[Mirpur Khas]] in Sindh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/ |title=Forced conversions of Pakistani Hindu girls - Daily Times |access-date=2020-02-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107045048/https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/ |archive-date=2020-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the study by the Birmingham University, nearly 3,000 forced conversions of minority women and girls took place in [[Pakistan]] during 2012-2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefridaytimes.com/marriages-and-conversions/|title=Marriages and Conversions|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the National (Catholic) Commission for Justice and Peace (NCJP), over 1,700 forced conversions happened between 2000 to 2012-mostly [[Hindus]] (726) and [[Christians]] (605).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefridaytimes.com/marriages-and-conversions/|title=Marriages and Conversions|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reports==\n*In 2003, a six-year-old Sikh girl was kidnapped by a member of the [[Afridi]] tribe in Northwest Frontier Province; the alleged kidnapper claimed the girl was actually 12-years-old, and had converted to Islam so therefore could not be returned to her non-Muslim family.<ref>{{cite book|title=Annual Report on International Religious Freedom, 2004|year=2005|publisher=[[United States Commission on International Religious Freedom]], [[State Dept (US)]], [[Senate Committee on Foreign Relations]] (US)|page=667|chapter= Pakistan |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=04dlwzB2SvcC&pg=PA667|isbn=978-0-16072-552-4|title-link=Annual Report on International Religious Freedom}}</ref>\n\n*On January 4th, 2005, 16 year old Hemi and 18 year old Marvi were kidnapped from Kunri village in Umerkot district.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*On March 3, 2005, 14 year old Raji was kidnapped from Aslam Town Jhuddo in Mirpurkhas District.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*On December 22, 2005, 13 year old Mashu was kidnapped from Jhaluree village in Mirpur Khas District.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*On July 23, 2006, 15 year-old Pooja was kidnapped from Lyari town in Karachi District. A judge ruled that she should be released and although she was, she was kidnapped again and has been missing ever since.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*On August 2, 2006, 16 year old Komal was kidnapped from Hawks bay in Karachi District.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*On December 31, 2006, 17 year old Deepa was kidnapped from Tharparkar district in Sindh province.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*In May 2007, members of the Christian community of [[Charsadda]] in the [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|North West Frontier Province]] of Pakistan, close to the border of [[Afghanistan]], reported that they had received letters threatening bombings if they did not convert to Islam, and that the police were not taking their fears seriously.<ref name=\"Fox News\">{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,273075,00.html|title=Taliban Tells Pakistani Christians: Convert or Die|work=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=May 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515081338/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,273075,00.html|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\n*In 2008, a Hindu girl was kidnapped, beaten and raped for 20 days. She was forcibly converted from Hinduism to Islam and married against her wish and was then forced into prostitution. However, the police refused to lodge an FIR.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1197650/woman-speaks-of-forced-conversion-denial-to-lodge-fir-of-rape-trafficking|title=Woman speaks of forced conversion, denial to lodge FIR of rape, trafficking|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*In June 2009, [[International Christian Concern]] (ICC) reported the rape and killing of a Christian man in Pakistan, for refusing to convert to Islam.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,526126,00.html |title=Christian Man Raped, Murdered for Refusing to Convert to Islam, Family Says |publisher=FOX News |date=June 13, 2009 |first=Nora |last=Zimmett |accessdate=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514193533/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,526126,00.html |archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n*Rinkle Kumari, a 19-year Pakistani student, Lata Kumari, and Asha Kumari, a Hindu working in a beauty parlor, were allegedly forced to convert from Hinduism to Islam.<ref name=\"fridaytimesrinkle\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thefridaytimes.com/beta2/tft/article.php?issue=20120413&page=9 |title=Opinion: Rinkle Kumari \u2013 the new Marvi of Sindh by Marvi Sirmed |publisher=Thefridaytimes.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-05 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130203203818/http://www.thefridaytimes.com/beta2/tft/article.php?issue=20120413&page=9 |archive-date=2013-02-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=151043 |title=SC orders release of Rinkle Kumari, others |work=[[Pakistan Observer]]|date= April 19, 2012|accessdate=2012-06-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221063358/http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=151043 |archivedate=2014-02-21 }}</ref> Their cases were appealed all the way to the [[Supreme Court of Pakistan]]. The appeal was admitted but remained unheard ever after.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1256767/curbs-forced-conversion/|title=Curbs on forced conversion|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=7 December 2016|website=The Express Tribune}}</ref> Afterwards, Rinkle reportedly opted to stay with her new husband rather than return home.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*On September 23, 2014, Joti Kumari, a student of Electrical Engineering was kidnapped from Larkana City in Sindh District.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*A total of 57 Hindus converted in [[Pasrur]] during May 14\u201319. On May 14, 35 Hindus of the same family were forced to convert by their employer because his sales dropped after Muslims started boycotting his eatable items as they were prepared by Hindus as well as their persecution by the Muslim employees of neighbouring shops according to their relatives. Since the impoverished Hindus had no other way to earn and needed to keep the job to survive, they converted. 14 members of another family converted on May 17 since no one was employing them, later another Hindu man and his family of eight under pressure from Muslims converted to Islam to avoid their land being grabbed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/15970/57-hindus-convert-to-islam-in-10-days/|title=57 Hindus convert to Islam in 10 days|first=Abdul|last=Manan|date=25 May 2010|website=The Express Tribune|accessdate=9 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423025030/https://tribune.com.pk/story/15970/57-hindus-convert-to-islam-in-10-days/|archive-date=23 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*In 2017, the Sikh community in Hangu district of Pakistan\u2019s [[Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa]] province alleged that they were \u201cbeing forced to convert to Islam\u201d by a government official. Farid Chand Singh, who filed the complaint, has claimed that Assistant Commissioner Tehsil Tall Yaqoob Khan was allegedly forcing Sikhs to convert to Islam and the residents of Doaba area are being tortured religiously.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1585150/1-sikh-community-hangu-forced-convert/ |title=Sikh community in Hangu 'being forced to convert' {{!}} The Express Tribune |access-date=2020-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180121191413/https://tribune.com.pk/story/1585150/1-sikh-community-hangu-forced-convert/ |archive-date=2018-01-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n*On April 29, 2017, a 17 year old, Priya Kaur, a Sikh girl was kidnapped from Buner district.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*In June, 2017, 16-year-old Ravita Meghwar was kidnapped in Sindh.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*In 2017, a 16 year old Hindu girl was kidnapped by a man named Ali Nawaz while she was playing ,from the Umerkot district. She was kept in a place near the Sarhandi shrine where she was raped multiple times for three months.Her father complained in the Sindh High Court and the court ordered the Ali Nawaz and four other abductors to produce the girl in court.The abductors threatened her to tell in court that she changed my religion and married Ali Nawaz .If not, they threatened that they would kill her parents. In the high court, she told the truth about Ali Nawaz kidnapping and raping her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1515863|title=THE STRANGE CASE OF THE SILENT WOMEN|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*Hindu sisters Reena and Raveena became the face of forced religious conversion in Pakistan in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-07-26/pakistan-forced-marriage-islam-conversion-teenagers-kidnapped/11338314|title=Hindu sisters Reena and Raveena become face of forced religious conversion in Pakistan|date=25 July 2019|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref> It prompted the Indian External Affairs Ministry to ask Pakistan to submit a report about it.<ref name=\"incidents\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/2019/mar/31/brides-of-despair-1956753.html|title=Brides of Despair|date=31 March 2019|publisher=The New Indian Express|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*January, 2019, 16 year old Anusha Kumari was kidnapped and the Indian High Commission took up the matter, but no action was taken.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*A Sikh girl, kidnapped and married to a Muslim is yet to return home despite the Governor of Punjab assuring to send her back to her parents in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/pakistan-sikh-girl-kidnapped-and-married-to-muslim-yet-to-return-home-1603605-2019-09-26 |title=Pakistan: Sikh girl, kidnapped and married to Muslim, yet to return home|date=26 September 2019|publisher=India Today |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n*In 2020, Mehak Kumari a 15-year-old Hindu girl was kidnapped, forcibly converted and married to a Muslim man. She was later rescued by the police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/pak-hindu-girl-rescued-yet-to-return-to-family/articleshow/73452872.cms |title=Pak Hindu girl rescued, yet to return to family|date=21 January 2020|publisher=Bennett, Coleman and Co. Ltd. |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/pak-police-recover-minor-hindu-girl/articleshow/73462390.cms |title=Pak police recover minor Hindu girl |date=21 January 2020 |publisher=Bennett, Coleman and Co. Ltd. |accessdate=21 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122200757/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/pak-police-recover-minor-hindu-girl/articleshow/73462390.cms |archive-date=22 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Court ordered her to be sent to a Women's protection centre.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/pak-court-sends-15-yr-old-hindu-girl-to-women-protection-centre-after-forced-conversion-marriage-30519 |title=Pak court sends 15-yr-old Hindu girl to women protection centre after forced conversion, marriage |date=23 January 2020 |publisher=The Tribune |accessdate=25 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125030535/https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/pak-court-sends-15-yr-old-hindu-girl-to-women-protection-centre-after-forced-conversion-marriage-30519 |archive-date=25 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the court she said that she didn't want to convert and to be sent back to her parents' house.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/amritsar/dont-want-to-convert-will-stay-with-parents-minor-pakistan-hindu-girl/articleshow/73996972.cms|title=Don't want to convert, will stay with parents: Minor Pakistan Hindu girl|date=7 February 2020|publisher=Bennett, Coleman and Co. Ltd. |accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref> Soon after, Islamic clerics in Pakistan demanded the beheading of Mehak Kumari for renouncing Islam after being converted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/international/article/hindu-minor-girl-who-was-forcefully-converted-renounces-islam-pakistani-mullahs-demand-death-penalty/551192|title=Hindu minor girl who was forcefully converted renounces Islam; Pakistani mullahs demand death penalty|date=9 February 2020|publisher=Times Now News|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*A bride was allegedly kidnapped with the help of the police in January 2020 from her wedding and forcibly married to a Muslim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.com/articleshow/73659948.cms |title=Pak Hindu bride abducted, converted to Islam, forcibly married to Muslim man|date=27 January 2020|publisher=Bennett, Coleman and Co. Ltd. |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n*In 2020, a 14-year-old Christian girl was allegedly abducted, converted to Islam and married off to a Muslim man in Karachi. However in the court, the judges maintained that the girl has already had her first menstrual cycle and under the Islamic Shariah Law she should be considered an adult, making her marriage with her abductor legal and justified.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/pakistan-minor-girl-forced-abduction-conversion-judges-adult-claim-menstruation-period-1644205-2020-02-07 |title=She's an adult as she has had her 1st period: Pak judges on minor Catholic girl's forced conversion, marriage|date=7 February 2020|publisher=Bennett, Coleman and Co. Ltd. |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Attempts to introduce Legislation against Forced conversions==\nIn 2016, a bill against forced conversion of minority girls was passed unanimously by the [[Sindh]] Provisional Assembly. However, the bill failed to make it into law as the Governor returned the bill due to the pressure from the Islamist groups and parties like the [[Council of Islamic Ideology]] and [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]].<ref>https://www.birmingham.ac.uk/Documents/college-artslaw/ptr/ciforb/Forced-Conversions-and-Forced-Marriages-in-Sindh.pdf</ref><ref name=\"tribune.com.pk\">{{cite news |title=PPP lawmakers turn down bill against forced conversions |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2075311/1-ppp-lawmakers-turn-bill-forced-conversions/?amp=1 |date=9 October 2019 |newspaper=The Express Tribune|department=City: Karachi |agency=TNN |access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2018 general elections, the [[Pakistan People Party]] (PPP) 's election manifesto said that they will \"Prevent forced conversion through legislative measures\". The 2013 election manifesto of Pakistan Muslim League N(PMLN)  said \"Necessary legislative measures will be undertaken to ensure there is no forced conversion of religion in the guise of marriage\", but this was removed from the 2018  Election Manifesto. <ref>{{cite web |title=The Index of Religious Diversity and Inclusion in PAKISTAN|page=50,51|url=http://www.clj.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/The-Index-of-Religious-Diversity-and-Inclusion-in-Pakistan.pdf|archive-url=http://www.clj.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/The-Index-of-Religious-Diversity-and-Inclusion-in-Pakistan.pdf|archive-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, The Criminal Law (protection of minorities) Bill-a bill against forced conversion was proposed by Hindu politician [[Nand Kumar|Nand Kumar Goklani]] in the Sindh assembly, but was turned down by the ruling [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] lawmakers.<ref name=\"tribune.com.pk\"/>\n\nIn September 2019, two bills against forced conversion was moved in the Pakistan National assembly-\"The Prohibition of Forced Religious Conversion Bill 2019\" moved by [[Naveed Amir]](Christian member of National assembly), and \"The Protection of Persons Against Forced Religious Conversion Bill\" moved by [[Ramesh Kumar Vankwani]](Hindu member of National assembly). However these bills have been referred to the Council of Islamic Ideology for its expert opinion.<ref>{{cite news |title=MNA protests rejection of bill on evacuee trust board\u2019s composition|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1508143 |newspaper=Dawn|department=City: Karachi |agency=TNN |access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Existing rules===\nThe rules that could be used against the accused in the case of forced conversion of a minor girl:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1244684/caste-and-captivity-dalit-suffering-in-sindh|title=Caste and captivity: Dalit suffering in Sindh|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Child marriage under the Sindh Child Marriage Restraint Act 2013\n*Forced marriage under Section 498B of the Pakistan Penal Code (PPC) 1860\n*kidnapping, abducting or inducing a woman to compel for marriage etc under Section 365B of the PPC 1860\n*rape under sections 375 and 376 of the PPC 1860\n*kidnapping or abducting from lawful guardianship under Section 361 of the PPC\n*kidnapping or abducting a person under the age of fourteen under Section 364A of the PPC 1860\n*kidnapping or abducting in order to subject person to grievous hurt, slavery etc.\n*bonded labour under relevant sections of the Bonded Labour System (Abolition) Act 1992.\n\n==Response==\n*Hindu politician Bhawan Das claimed that his community can bear the looting and the kidnapping of Hindu men, but the kidnapping of the daughters and wives of his community was too painful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/08/forced-conversions-torment-pakistan-hindus-201481795524630505.html|title=Forced conversions torment Pakistan's Hindus|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Pakistan Prime Minister Imran Khan has condemned forced conversions and has called the practice as un-Islamic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/forced-conversions-are-un-islamic-says-imran-khan/article28750491.ece|title=Forced conversions are \u2018un-Islamic\u2019, says Imran Khan|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hinduism in Pakistan]]\n* [[Christianity in Pakistan]]\n* [[Blasphemy in Pakistan]]\n* [[Persecution of Hindus]]\n* [[Freedom of religion in Pakistan]]\n* [[Islamization in Pakistan]]\n* [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan]]\n* [[Pakistan Movement]]\n* [[Religion in Pakistan]]\n* [[Religious discrimination in Pakistan]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Forced religious conversion]]\n[[Category:Islamization]]\n[[Category:Persecution of Christians in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Religiously motivated violence in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Dargah_pir_sarhandi.jpg|thumb|Dargah pir sarhandi, a frequent crime scene of forced conversion and marriage of kidnapped underage Hindu girls.]]\n\nIn [[Pakistan]], girls belonging to the minority [[Hindu]], [[Sikh]], and [[Christianity|Christian]] communities are kidnapped, raped, [[Forced conversion|forcibly converted]] to [[Islam]], and married to [[Muslim]] men.<ref name=aljazeera2014-08-18>{{cite news | url = https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/08/forced-conversions-torment-pakistan-hindus-201481795524630505.html | author = Maham Javaid | title = Forced conversions torment Pakistan's Hindus | work = [[Aljazeera]] | accessdate=27 January 2020 | url-status = live | archivedate = 2014-08-19 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140819234717/https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/08/forced-conversions-torment-pakistan-hindus-201481795524630505.html | quote = According to a report from the Movement for Solidarity and Peace, about 1,000 non-Muslim girls are converted to Islam each year in Pakistan. Every month, an estimated 20 or more Hindu girls are abducted and converted, although exact figures are impossible to gather, said Amarnath Motumal, the vice chairperson of the Human Rights Commission of Pakistan (HRCP).}}</ref> These girls are generally 12 to 18 years old.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia-pacific/new-law-may-help-forced-conversions-pakistani-hindu-girls|title=May Help With Forced Conversions of Pakistani Hindu Girls|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> According to The Centre for Social Justice and Peoples Commission for Minorities\u2019 Rights, a majority of the victims of forced conversion are minor girls as young as 12 years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1548550/forced-conversions|title=Forced conversions|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nEvery year, about 1,000 non-Muslim girls are forcibly converted to Islam in Pakistan.<ref name=thenews2015-07-15>{{Cite news | url = https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/51401-1000-girls-forcibly-converted-to-islam-in-pakistan-every-year | title = 1,000 girls forcibly converted to Islam in Pakistan every year | work = [[The News International|The News]] | date = 2015-07-15 | accessdate=27 January 2020 | url-status = live | archivedate = 2019-09-20 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20190920210516/https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/51401-1000-girls-forcibly-converted-to-islam-in-pakistan-every-year | quote = With the growing intolerance in Pakistani society of religious minorities, evidenced by the increased violence, murder and persecution of religious minorities in the country, forced conversions have emerged as a disturbing trend. }}</ref> The [[United Nations Human Rights Council|Human Rights Council of Pakistan]] has reported that cases of forced conversion are increasing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/51826ef842.html|title=Refworld \u2013 USCIRF Annual Report 2013 \u2013 Countries of Particular Concern: Pakistan|author=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|work=Refworld|date=30 April 2013|accessdate=May 5, 2015|author-link=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217090031/http://www.refworld.org/docid/51826ef842.html|archive-date=17 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada\">{{cite web | url=https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/03/04/PAK104258.E.pdf | title=Pakistan: Religious conversion, including treatment of converts and forced conversions (2009\u20132012) | publisher=Government Research Directorate, [[Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada]] | work=Responses to Information Requests | date= January 14, 2013 | accessdate=January 17, 2018| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504144820/https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/03/04/PAK104258.E.pdf| archivedate=May 4, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to the [[Pakistan Hindu Council]], forced religious conversions are one of the main reasons for migration of Hindus from Pakistan to [[India]].<ref name=usatoday2017-02-15>{{cite news | title = Pakistani Hindus lose daughters to forced Muslim marriages | url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2017/02/15/pakistani-hindus-lose-daughters-forced-muslim-marriages/97013614/ | work = [[USA Today]] | author = Naila Inayat | location = [[Lahore]] | accessdate = 29 January 2020 | url-status = live | archivedate = 2020-01-29 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200129195225/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2017/02/15/pakistani-hindus-lose-daughters-forced-muslim-marriages/97013614/ | quote = The police refused to intervene. Her kidnapper told them she ran away from home, and converted to Islam and married him voluntarily. But after her family pressured a court to intervene, she told judges the truth and they freed her. }}</ref> \n\n[[Sharia|Islamic law]] prohibits forced conversion, following the Quranic principle that there is \"[[Al-Baqara 256|no compulsion in religion]]\" (2:256),<ref name=bonner>{{cite book|author=Michael Bonner|title=Jihad in Islamic History|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2008|pages= 89\u201390|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qxq7eykoJgoC&pg=PA89|quote=To begin with, there was no forced conversion, no choice between \"Islam and the Sword\". Islamic law, following a clear Quranic principle (2:256), prohibited any such things [...] although there have been instances of forced conversion in Islamic history, these have been exceptional.|isbn=978-1400827381}}</ref><ref>Winter, T. J., & Williams, J. A. (2002). ''Understanding Islam and the Muslims: The Muslim Family Islam and World Peace''. Louisville, Kentucky: Fons Vitae. p. 82. {{ISBN|978-1-887752-47-3}}. Quote: The laws of Muslim warfare forbid any forced conversions, and regard them as invalid if they occur.</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|last1 = A.C. Brown|first1 = Jonathan|authorlink = Jonathan A.C. Brown|title = Misquoting Muhammad: The Challenge and Choices of Interpreting the Prophet's Legacy|date = 2014|publisher = [[Oneworld Publications]]|isbn = 978-1-78074-420-9|page = [https://archive.org/details/misquotingmuhamm0000brow/page/92 92]|chapter = 3. The Fragile Truth Of Scripture|quote = 'No compulsion in religion' (2:256) was a Qur'anic command revealed in Medina when a child from one of the Muslim families who had been educated in the town's Jewish schools decided to depart with the Jewish tribe being expelled from Medina. His distraught parents were told by God and the Prophet in this verse that they could not compel their son to stay. The verse, however, has been understood over the centuries as a general command that people cannot be forced to convert to Islam.|chapter-url = https://archive.org/details/misquotingmuhamm0000brow|url = https://archive.org/details/misquotingmuhamm0000brow/page/92}}</ref> but episodes of [[forced conversion]]s are recorded in the [[history of Islam]].\n\nThe majority of reported incidents have taken place in the [[Sindh]] province.{{efn|Sindh is the [[Hinduism in Pakistan#Hindu population by province|only province]] of Pakistan that has a substantial number of Hindus. The Hindus in other provinces constitute small fractions of 1 percent.<ref>[http://www.pbs.gov.pk/sites/default/files/tables/POPULATION%20BY%20RELIGION.pdf Population by religion], Pakistan Bureau of Statstics. Retrieved 3 February 2020. Also reproduced at [https://www.scribd.com/document/400843609/Pakisatn-Bearu-of-Statistics-Population-by-Religion-pdf scribd.com].</ref>}}The [[Sindh]] legislature passed a law in 2016 outlawing forcible conversions and conversions before the age of 18, but the Governor refused to sign it into Act, ostensibly under pressure from Muslim fundamentalist groups. The Sindh province circa 2017 had over seven percent population of Hindus, including [[Dalit]]s.<ref name=\"Atlantic\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/08/hindu-muslim-pakistan/536238/|title=Hindu Today, Muslim Tomorrow|publisher=[[The Atlantic]]|last=Imtiaz|first=Saba|date=14 August 2017|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nReligious institutions like Bharchundi Sharif and Sarhandi Pir support forced conversions and are known to have the support and protection of ruling political parties of Sindh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2020-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107045048/https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/ |archive-date=2020-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to victims\u2019 families and activists, [[Abdul Haq (politician)|Abdul Haq (Mitthu Mian)]] who is a  politician and caretaker of [[Daharki#Religion|Bharachundi Sharif Dargah]] in [[Ghotki district]] and Pir Ayub Jan Sirhindi who is the caretaker of Dargah pir sarhandi in [[Umerkot District]] have supported forced conversions and are known to have the support and protection of the ruling political parties of Sindh.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/|title=Forced conversions of Pakistani Hindu girls|date=19 September 2017|publisher=|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://religionnews.com/2019/06/06/forced-conversions-marriages-spike-in-pakistan/|title=Forced conversions, marriages spike in Pakistan|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191106185952/https://religionnews.com/2019/06/06/forced-conversions-marriages-spike-in-pakistan/|archive-date=2019-11-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the National Commission of Justice and Peace and the [[Pakistan Hindu Council]] (PHC) around 1000 Hindu and Christian minority women are converted to Islam and then forcibly married off to their abductors or rapists. This practice is being reported increasingly in the districts of [[Tharparkar]], [[Umerkot]], and [[Mirpur Khas]] in Sindh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/ |title=Forced conversions of Pakistani Hindu girls - Daily Times |access-date=2020-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107045048/https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/ |archive-date=2020-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> The actual number of cases are estimated to be higher as most of the cases go unreported.<ref>{{cite news|title=Another Hindu temple vandalised in Pakistan, holy books, idols burnt|url=https://www.wionews.com/pakistan/another-hindu-temple-vandalised-in-pakistan-holy-books-idols-burnt-276834|date=2 August 2017|access-date=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127090709/https://www.wionews.com/pakistan/another-hindu-temple-vandalised-in-pakistan-holy-books-idols-burnt-276834|archive-date=27 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the report by the Minority Rights commission, the forced conversions and forced marriages is on the rise in South Punjab, particularly in [[Rahim Yar Khan District|Rahim Yar Khan]] and adjacent areas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/430418/intolerance-growing-in-south-punjab-report/?amp=1|title=Intolerance growing in South Punjab: Report|access-date=8 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020 forced conversions continue in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1548550/forced-conversions  |title=Forced conversions |author=Jahangir, Sulema|date=April 2020|work=Dawn|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Details==\nFirst, underage girls are abducted from their home or where they work, later they re-appear after having been married off to a Muslim. They are often raped and then forcibly converted to Islam. To prevent them from going back home or reporting the rape to the police, the girls are forcibly married to the perpetrators. Reports obtained by the NGO [[Global Human Rights Defence]] indicate that the perpetrators will often put a fake age of the girl on the marriage certificate to hide that she is underage. When the family of the girl tries to report this to the police, they are often met by biased officers who refuse to file an FIR (First Information Report). The conversions are backed by powerful religious instititutions and leaders who also offer incentives to people to convert. Moreover, the perpetrators will often force the victim to sign a report saying that she converted and married out of her own free will, hindering the attempts of the family to have their girl returned to them. Additionally, the perpetrators will often file counter-suits against the victim's family for harassment and for attempting to convert the girl back to her former religion.<ref>{{cite web |title=Human rights report 2019|url=https://ghrdorg.files.wordpress.com/2019/03/report-ghrd-2019.pdf|format=PDF|access-date=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://ghrdorg.files.wordpress.com/2019/03/report-ghrd-2019.pdf|archive-date=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Human rights report 2019|url=https://eptoday.com/files/Religious%20Minorities%20Report.pdf|format=PDF|access-date=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://eptoday.com/files/Religious%20Minorities%20Report.pdf|archive-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to senior journalist Shahzeb Jillani, under-age girls from poor farming communities are especially vulnerable to conversions, he says, \u201cWealthy Muslim farmers see them as fair game for abductions, rape, and prolonged sexual exploitation in captivity. Some notorious religious establishments proudly validate these alleged crimes. State institutions, the police and politicians have encouraged the trend by looking the other way.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/in-pakistan-the-problem-of-forced-conversions/article26823108.ece |title=In Pakistan, the problem of forced conversions|publisher=The Hindu|last=Sarfraz|first=Mehmal|date=13 April 2019|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\nMany people believe that so-called voluntary conversions and marriages are in fact legal cover for the kidnappers, whose young victims fear for their lives and their families\u2019 if they speak the truth publicly.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistan: Hindu Sisters Not Forcibly Converted to Islam |url=https://www.voanews.com/extremism-watch/pakistan-hindu-sisters-not-forcibly-converted-islam |accessdate=13 February 2020 |work=VoA |date=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Human Rights Commission of Pakistan]] found that many girls who had been presumed to have eloped had actually been kidnapped, and were later sold or forced to marry Muslim men. When the young, abducted, Hindu girl who has been forced to convert to Islam appears in court, the fanatics create a great brouhaha and follow her into the building due to which she gets intimidated and is unable to speak<ref name=\"Eloped\">{{cite news |title=Sindh's Stolen Brides |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/sindhs-stolen-brides/229886 |accessdate=14 February 2020 |work=Outlook |date=23 January 2006 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Abdul Hai of the Human Rights Commission of Pakistan, forced conversion of lower caste Hindus is taking place in large numbers but is going unreported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1244684/caste-and-captivity-dalit-suffering-in-sindh|title=Caste and captivity: Dalit suffering in Sindh|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nAccording to the Dalit activist Surendar Valasai, every year around 1,000 to 1,200 Dalit Hindu girls are kidnapped and forcibly converted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1244684/caste-and-captivity-dalit-suffering-in-sindh|title=Caste and captivity: Dalit suffering in Sindh|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nA 2014 report by the Movement for Solidarity and Peace (MSP) says about 1,000 [[women in Pakistan]] are forcibly converted to Islam every year.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anwar|first1=Iqbal|title=1,000 minority girls forced in marriage every year: report|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1098452|website=Dawn|accessdate=25 July 2014|date=2014-04-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140615062301/http://www.dawn.com/news/1098452|archive-date=15 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dunya|first1=Author|title=India ruling party chief urges law against religious conversions|url=http://dunyanews.tv/index.php/en/World/251054-India-ruling-party-chief-urges-law-against-religio|website=[[Dunya News]] |date=20 December 2014|accessdate=20 December 2014|location=New Delhi |agency=[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]]}}</ref> \n\nAccording to Amarnath Motumal, the vice chairperson of the [[Human Rights Commission of Pakistan]], every month, an estimated 20 or more [[Hindu]] girls are abducted and converted, although exact figures are impossible to gather.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/08/forced-conversions-torment-pakistan-hindus-201481795524630505.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2020-01-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629081246/https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/08/forced-conversions-torment-pakistan-hindus-201481795524630505.html |archive-date=2019-06-29 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2014 alone, 265 legal cases of forced conversion were reported mostly involving [[Hindu]] girls.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1170682 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2020-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106221530/https://www.dawn.com/news/1170682 |archive-date=2020-01-06 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the National Commission of Justice and Peace and the [[Pakistan Hindu Council]] (PHC) around 1000 Christian and Hindu minority women are converted to Islam and then forcibly married off to their abductors or rapists. This practice is being reported increasingly in the districts of [[Tharparkar]], [[Umerkot]], and [[Mirpur Khas]] in Sindh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/ |title=Forced conversions of Pakistani Hindu girls - Daily Times |access-date=2020-02-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107045048/https://dailytimes.com.pk/116289/forced-conversions-of-pakistani-hindu-girls/ |archive-date=2020-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the study by the Birmingham University, nearly 3,000 forced conversions of minority women and girls took place in [[Pakistan]] during 2012-2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefridaytimes.com/marriages-and-conversions/|title=Marriages and Conversions|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the National (Catholic) Commission for Justice and Peace (NCJP), over 1,700 forced conversions happened between 2000 to 2012-mostly [[Hindus]] (726) and [[Christians]] (605).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefridaytimes.com/marriages-and-conversions/|title=Marriages and Conversions|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reports==\n*In 2003, a six-year-old Sikh girl was kidnapped by a member of the [[Afridi]] tribe in Northwest Frontier Province; the alleged kidnapper claimed the girl was actually 12-years-old, and had converted to Islam so therefore could not be returned to her non-Muslim family.<ref>{{cite book|title=Annual Report on International Religious Freedom, 2004|year=2005|publisher=[[United States Commission on International Religious Freedom]], [[State Dept (US)]], [[Senate Committee on Foreign Relations]] (US)|page=667|chapter= Pakistan |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=04dlwzB2SvcC&pg=PA667|isbn=978-0-16072-552-4|title-link=Annual Report on International Religious Freedom}}</ref>\n\n*On January 4th, 2005, 16 year old Hemi and 18 year old Marvi were kidnapped from Kunri village in Umerkot district.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*On March 3, 2005, 14 year old Raji was kidnapped from Aslam Town Jhuddo in Mirpurkhas District.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*On December 22, 2005, 13 year old Mashu was kidnapped from Jhaluree village in Mirpur Khas District.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*On July 23, 2006, 15 year-old Pooja was kidnapped from Lyari town in Karachi District. A judge ruled that she should be released and although she was, she was kidnapped again and has been missing ever since.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*On August 2, 2006, 16 year old Komal was kidnapped from Hawks bay in Karachi District.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*On December 31, 2006, 17 year old Deepa was kidnapped from Tharparkar district in Sindh province.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*In May 2007, members of the Christian community of [[Charsadda]] in the [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|North West Frontier Province]] of Pakistan, close to the border of [[Afghanistan]], reported that they had received letters threatening bombings if they did not convert to Islam, and that the police were not taking their fears seriously.<ref name=\"Fox News\">{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,273075,00.html|title=Taliban Tells Pakistani Christians: Convert or Die|work=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=May 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515081338/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,273075,00.html|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\n*In 2008, a Hindu girl was kidnapped, beaten and raped for 20 days. She was forcibly converted from Hinduism to Islam and married against her wish and was then forced into prostitution. However, the police refused to lodge an FIR.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1197650/woman-speaks-of-forced-conversion-denial-to-lodge-fir-of-rape-trafficking|title=Woman speaks of forced conversion, denial to lodge FIR of rape, trafficking|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*In June 2009, [[International Christian Concern]] (ICC) reported the rape and killing of a Christian man in Pakistan, for refusing to convert to Islam.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,526126,00.html |title=Christian Man Raped, Murdered for Refusing to Convert to Islam, Family Says |publisher=FOX News |date=June 13, 2009 |first=Nora |last=Zimmett |accessdate=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514193533/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,526126,00.html |archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n*Rinkle Kumari, a 19-year Pakistani student, Lata Kumari, and Asha Kumari, a Hindu working in a beauty parlor, were allegedly forced to convert from Hinduism to Islam.<ref name=\"fridaytimesrinkle\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thefridaytimes.com/beta2/tft/article.php?issue=20120413&page=9 |title=Opinion: Rinkle Kumari \u2013 the new Marvi of Sindh by Marvi Sirmed |publisher=Thefridaytimes.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-05 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130203203818/http://www.thefridaytimes.com/beta2/tft/article.php?issue=20120413&page=9 |archive-date=2013-02-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=151043 |title=SC orders release of Rinkle Kumari, others |work=[[Pakistan Observer]]|date= April 19, 2012|accessdate=2012-06-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221063358/http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=151043 |archivedate=2014-02-21 }}</ref> Their cases were appealed all the way to the [[Supreme Court of Pakistan]]. The appeal was admitted but remained unheard ever after.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1256767/curbs-forced-conversion/|title=Curbs on forced conversion|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=7 December 2016|website=The Express Tribune}}</ref> Afterwards, Rinkle reportedly opted to stay with her new husband rather than return home.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*On September 23, 2014, Joti Kumari, a student of Electrical Engineering was kidnapped from Larkana City in Sindh District.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*A total of 57 Hindus converted in [[Pasrur]] during May 14\u201319. On May 14, 35 Hindus of the same family were forced to convert by their employer because his sales dropped after Muslims started boycotting his eatable items as they were prepared by Hindus as well as their persecution by the Muslim employees of neighbouring shops according to their relatives. Since the impoverished Hindus had no other way to earn and needed to keep the job to survive, they converted. 14 members of another family converted on May 17 since no one was employing them, later another Hindu man and his family of eight under pressure from Muslims converted to Islam to avoid their land being grabbed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/15970/57-hindus-convert-to-islam-in-10-days/|title=57 Hindus convert to Islam in 10 days|first=Abdul|last=Manan|date=25 May 2010|website=The Express Tribune|accessdate=9 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423025030/https://tribune.com.pk/story/15970/57-hindus-convert-to-islam-in-10-days/|archive-date=23 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*In 2017, the Sikh community in Hangu district of Pakistan\u2019s [[Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa]] province alleged that they were \u201cbeing forced to convert to Islam\u201d by a government official. Farid Chand Singh, who filed the complaint, has claimed that Assistant Commissioner Tehsil Tall Yaqoob Khan was allegedly forcing Sikhs to convert to Islam and the residents of Doaba area are being tortured religiously.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1585150/1-sikh-community-hangu-forced-convert/ |title=Sikh community in Hangu 'being forced to convert' {{!}} The Express Tribune |access-date=2020-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180121191413/https://tribune.com.pk/story/1585150/1-sikh-community-hangu-forced-convert/ |archive-date=2018-01-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n*On April 29, 2017, a 17 year old, Priya Kaur, a Sikh girl was kidnapped from Buner district.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*In June, 2017, 16-year-old Ravita Meghwar was kidnapped in Sindh.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*In 2017, a 16 year old Hindu girl was kidnapped by a man named Ali Nawaz while she was playing ,from the Umerkot district. She was kept in a place near the Sarhandi shrine where she was raped multiple times for three months.Her father complained in the Sindh High Court and the court ordered the Ali Nawaz and four other abductors to produce the girl in court.The abductors threatened her to tell in court that she changed my religion and married Ali Nawaz .If not, they threatened that they would kill her parents. In the high court, she told the truth about Ali Nawaz kidnapping and raping her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1515863|title=THE STRANGE CASE OF THE SILENT WOMEN|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*Hindu sisters Reena and Raveena became the face of forced religious conversion in Pakistan in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-07-26/pakistan-forced-marriage-islam-conversion-teenagers-kidnapped/11338314|title=Hindu sisters Reena and Raveena become face of forced religious conversion in Pakistan|date=25 July 2019|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref> It prompted the Indian External Affairs Ministry to ask Pakistan to submit a report about it.<ref name=\"incidents\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/2019/mar/31/brides-of-despair-1956753.html|title=Brides of Despair|date=31 March 2019|publisher=The New Indian Express|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*January, 2019, 16 year old Anusha Kumari was kidnapped and the Indian High Commission took up the matter, but no action was taken.<ref name=\"incidents\" />\n\n*A Sikh girl, kidnapped and married to a Muslim is yet to return home despite the Governor of Punjab assuring to send her back to her parents in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/pakistan-sikh-girl-kidnapped-and-married-to-muslim-yet-to-return-home-1603605-2019-09-26 |title=Pakistan: Sikh girl, kidnapped and married to Muslim, yet to return home|date=26 September 2019|publisher=India Today |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n*In 2020, Mehak Kumari a 15-year-old Hindu girl was kidnapped, forcibly converted and married to a Muslim man. She was later rescued by the police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/pak-hindu-girl-rescued-yet-to-return-to-family/articleshow/73452872.cms |title=Pak Hindu girl rescued, yet to return to family|date=21 January 2020|publisher=Bennett, Coleman and Co. Ltd. |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/pak-police-recover-minor-hindu-girl/articleshow/73462390.cms |title=Pak police recover minor Hindu girl |date=21 January 2020 |publisher=Bennett, Coleman and Co. Ltd. |accessdate=21 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122200757/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/pak-police-recover-minor-hindu-girl/articleshow/73462390.cms |archive-date=22 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Court ordered her to be sent to a Women's protection centre.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/pak-court-sends-15-yr-old-hindu-girl-to-women-protection-centre-after-forced-conversion-marriage-30519 |title=Pak court sends 15-yr-old Hindu girl to women protection centre after forced conversion, marriage |date=23 January 2020 |publisher=The Tribune |accessdate=25 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125030535/https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/pak-court-sends-15-yr-old-hindu-girl-to-women-protection-centre-after-forced-conversion-marriage-30519 |archive-date=25 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the court she said that she didn't want to convert and to be sent back to her parents' house.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/amritsar/dont-want-to-convert-will-stay-with-parents-minor-pakistan-hindu-girl/articleshow/73996972.cms|title=Don't want to convert, will stay with parents: Minor Pakistan Hindu girl|date=7 February 2020|publisher=Bennett, Coleman and Co. Ltd. |accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref> Soon after, Islamic clerics in Pakistan demanded the beheading of Mehak Kumari for renouncing Islam after being converted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/international/article/hindu-minor-girl-who-was-forcefully-converted-renounces-islam-pakistani-mullahs-demand-death-penalty/551192|title=Hindu minor girl who was forcefully converted renounces Islam; Pakistani mullahs demand death penalty|date=9 February 2020|publisher=Times Now News|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*A bride was allegedly kidnapped with the help of the police in January 2020 from her wedding and forcibly married to a Muslim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.com/articleshow/73659948.cms |title=Pak Hindu bride abducted, converted to Islam, forcibly married to Muslim man|date=27 January 2020|publisher=Bennett, Coleman and Co. Ltd. |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n*In 2020, a 14-year-old Christian girl was allegedly abducted, converted to Islam and married off to a Muslim man in Karachi. However in the court, the judges maintained that the girl has already had her first menstrual cycle and under the Islamic Shariah Law she should be considered an adult, making her marriage with her abductor legal and justified.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/pakistan-minor-girl-forced-abduction-conversion-judges-adult-claim-menstruation-period-1644205-2020-02-07 |title=She's an adult as she has had her 1st period: Pak judges on minor Catholic girl's forced conversion, marriage|date=7 February 2020|publisher=Bennett, Coleman and Co. Ltd. |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Attempts to introduce Legislation against Forced conversions==\nIn 2016, a bill against forced conversion of minority girls was passed unanimously by the [[Sindh]] Provisional Assembly. However, the bill failed to make it into law as the Governor returned the bill due to the pressure from the Islamist groups and parties like the [[Council of Islamic Ideology]] and [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]].<ref>https://www.birmingham.ac.uk/Documents/college-artslaw/ptr/ciforb/Forced-Conversions-and-Forced-Marriages-in-Sindh.pdf</ref><ref name=\"tribune.com.pk\">{{cite news |title=PPP lawmakers turn down bill against forced conversions |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2075311/1-ppp-lawmakers-turn-bill-forced-conversions/?amp=1 |date=9 October 2019 |newspaper=The Express Tribune|department=City: Karachi |agency=TNN |access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2018 general elections, the [[Pakistan People Party]] (PPP) 's election manifesto said that they will \"Prevent forced conversion through legislative measures\". The 2013 election manifesto of Pakistan Muslim League N(PMLN)  said \"Necessary legislative measures will be undertaken to ensure there is no forced conversion of religion in the guise of marriage\", but this was removed from the 2018  Election Manifesto. <ref>{{cite web |title=The Index of Religious Diversity and Inclusion in PAKISTAN|page=50,51|url=http://www.clj.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/The-Index-of-Religious-Diversity-and-Inclusion-in-Pakistan.pdf|archive-url=http://www.clj.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/The-Index-of-Religious-Diversity-and-Inclusion-in-Pakistan.pdf|archive-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, The Criminal Law (protection of minorities) Bill-a bill against forced conversion was proposed by Hindu politician [[Nand Kumar|Nand Kumar Goklani]] in the Sindh assembly, but was turned down by the ruling [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] lawmakers.<ref name=\"tribune.com.pk\"/>\n\nIn September 2019, two bills against forced conversion was moved in the Pakistan National assembly-\"The Prohibition of Forced Religious Conversion Bill 2019\" moved by [[Naveed Amir]](Christian member of National assembly), and \"The Protection of Persons Against Forced Religious Conversion Bill\" moved by [[Ramesh Kumar Vankwani]](Hindu member of National assembly). However these bills have been referred to the Council of Islamic Ideology for its expert opinion.<ref>{{cite news |title=MNA protests rejection of bill on evacuee trust board\u2019s composition|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1508143 |newspaper=Dawn|department=City: Karachi |agency=TNN |access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Existing rules===\nThe rules that could be used against the accused in the case of forced conversion of a minor girl:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1244684/caste-and-captivity-dalit-suffering-in-sindh|title=Caste and captivity: Dalit suffering in Sindh|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Child marriage under the Sindh Child Marriage Restraint Act 2013\n*Forced marriage under Section 498B of the Pakistan Penal Code (PPC) 1860\n*kidnapping, abducting or inducing a woman to compel for marriage etc under Section 365B of the PPC 1860\n*rape under sections 375 and 376 of the PPC 1860\n*kidnapping or abducting from lawful guardianship under Section 361 of the PPC\n*kidnapping or abducting a person under the age of fourteen under Section 364A of the PPC 1860\n*kidnapping or abducting in order to subject person to grievous hurt, slavery etc.\n*bonded labour under relevant sections of the Bonded Labour System (Abolition) Act 1992.\n\n==Response==\n*Hindu politician Bhawan Das claimed that his community can bear the looting and the kidnapping of Hindu men, but the kidnapping of the daughters and wives of his community was too painful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/08/forced-conversions-torment-pakistan-hindus-201481795524630505.html|title=Forced conversions torment Pakistan's Hindus|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Pakistan Prime Minister Imran Khan has condemned forced conversions and has called the practice as un-Islamic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/forced-conversions-are-un-islamic-says-imran-khan/article28750491.ece|title=Forced conversions are \u2018un-Islamic\u2019, says Imran Khan|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hinduism in Pakistan]]\n* [[Christianity in Pakistan]]\n* [[Blasphemy in Pakistan]]\n* [[Persecution of Hindus]]\n* [[Freedom of religion in Pakistan]]\n* [[Islamization in Pakistan]]\n* [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan]]\n* [[Pakistan Movement]]\n* [[Religion in Pakistan]]\n* [[Religious discrimination in Pakistan]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Forced religious conversion]]\n[[Category:Islamization]]\n[[Category:Persecution of Christians in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Religiously motivated violence in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "120.21.1.227", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forced_conversion_to_Islam_in_Pakistan"}
